{"title_page": "Jay Wilsey", "text_new": "{{short description|American actor}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Jay Wilsey\n| image        = Jaywilsey.gif\n| caption      = Wilsey in ''[[Texas Terror (film)|Texas Terror]]'', 1935\n| birth_date   = {{birth date|1896|2|6}}\n| birth_place  = [[Hillsdale, Missouri]], U.S.\n| death_date   = {{death date and age|1961|10|25|1896|2|6}}\n| death_place  = [[Los Angeles, California]], U.S.\n| occupation   = Actor\n| yearsactive  = 1924-1944\n| spouse       = Jeanette Boutelle (1933-1961) (his death)\n}}\n'''Jay Wilsey''' (February 6, 1896 &ndash; October 25, 1961) was an American film actor (born Wilbert Jay Wilsey). He appeared in nearly 100 films between 1924 and 1944. He starred in a series of very low-budget westerns in the 1920s and 1930s, billed as '''Buffalo Bill Jr.''' \n\nBorn in [[St. Francisville, Missouri]], Wilsey rode in Wild West shows and rodeos before he became an actor. His first film was ''Rarin' to Go'' (1924).<ref>{{cite book |last1=Freese |first1=Gene Scott |title=Hollywood Stunt Performers, 1910s-1970s: A Biographical Dictionary, 2d ed. |date=2014 |publisher=McFarland |isbn=978-1-4766-1470-0 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=OLpqAwAAQBAJ&pg=RA3-PA1986&dq=%22Jay+Wilsey%22&hl=en&newbks=1&newbks_redir=0&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwibqN3TgoLnAhUugK0KHeS1DXoQ6AEwA3oECAYQAg#v=onepage&q=%22Jay%20Wilsey%22&f=false |accessdate=January 14, 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Wilsey's career as an actor diminished as sound films increased in popularity, causing him to become a stunt performer. A January 29, 1940, newspaper article reported that he had performed 6,000 stunts up to that time.<ref name=\"lat\">{{cite news |title=Film Stunt Man and Wife, Ex-Actress, Plan Dream Cruise |url=https://www.newspapers.com/clip/35319324/jay_wilsey/ |accessdate=August 27, 2019 |work=The Los Angeles Times |date=January 29, 1940 |location=California, Los Angeles |page=11|via = [[Newspapers.com]]}}</ref>\n\nWilsey was married to actress Jeanette Boutelle.<ref name=lat/>\n\n==Selected filmography==\n{{div col|colwidth=25em}}\n* ''Rarin' to Go'' (1924) - Bill Dillon\n* ''[[Fast and Fearless]]'' (1924) - Lightning Bill Lewis\n* ''Hard Hittin' Hamilton'' (1924) - Bill Hamilton\n* ''Bringin' Home the Bacon'' (1924) - Bill Winton\n* ''Thundering Romance'' (1924) - Lightning Bill\n* ''[[Full Speed (1925 film)|Full Speed]]'' (1925)\n* ''On the Go'' (1925) - Bill Drake\n* ''Double Action Daniels'' (1925) - Double Action Daniels\n* ''Quicker'n Lightnin''' (1925) - Quicker'n Lightnin'\n* ''The Desert Demon'' (1925) - Bill Davis\n* ''The Saddle Cyclone'' (1925) - Bill Demming\n* ''A Streak of Luck'' (1925) - Billy Burton\n* ''The Roaring Rider'' (1926) - Buffalo Bill Jr.\n* ''Hoodoo Ranch'' (1926)\n* ''Trumpin' Trouble'' (1926) - Bill Lawson\n* ''Coming an' Going'' (1926) - Bill Martin\n* ''[[Deuce High]]'' (1926) - Ted Crawford\n* ''[[Rawhide (1926 film)|Rawhide]]'' (1926) - Rawhide Rawlins\n* ''Speedy Spurs'' (1926) - Bill Clark\n* ''[[The Bonanza Buckaroo]]'' (1926) - Bill Merritt\n* ''[[Bad Man's Bluff]]'' (1926) - Zane Castleton\n* ''[[The Galloping Gobs]]'' (1927) - Bill Corbitt\n* ''The Ridin' Rowdy'' (1927) - Bill Gibson\n* ''Pals in Peril'' (1927) - Bill Gordon\n* ''[[The Interferin' Gent]]'' (1927) - Bill Stannard\n* ''[[The Obligin' Buckaroo]]'' (1927) - Bill Murray\n* ''Roarin' Broncs'' (1927) - Bill Morris\n* ''[[The Ballyhoo Buster]]'' (1928) - Bob Warner\n* ''[[The Valley of Hunted Men]]'' (1928) - Tom Mallory\n* ''[[A Final Reckoning]]'' (1928) - Captain Wilson\n* ''[[The Pirate of Panama]]'' (1929) - Karl\n* ''[[Thundering Thompson]]'' (1929) - Cowhand (uncredited)\n* ''Bar-L Ranch'' (1930) - Bob Tyler\n* ''Beyond the Rio Grande'' (1930) - Bill\n* ''The Cheyenne Kid'' (1930) - Buck Allen / The Cheyenne Kid\n* ''[[Way Out West (1930 film)|Way Out West]]'' (1930) - Hank\n* ''Beyond the Law'' (1930) - Henchman (uncredited)\n* ''[[The Utah Kid (1930 film)|The Utah Kid]]