m\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| \n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| \n|-\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 2000/01\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 11.9m\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 2008/09\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 15.0m\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 2016/17\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 12.6m\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| \n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| \n|-\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 2001/02\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 11.4m\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 2009/10\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 14.7m\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 2017/18\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 12.3m\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| \n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| \n|-\n| colspan=\"11\" style=\"background:#fff; font-size:90%;\"|Estimates from the [[Department for Transport]]<ref name=\"dftjour\">{{cite web |title=Passenger journeys on light rail and trams by system: England - annual from 1983/84 |url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/719478/lrt0101.ods |publisher=Department For Transport |accessdate=14 June 2019 |format=downloadable .ods [[OpenDocument]] file}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Future, past plans, delays and cost overruns==\nThe proposed extensions to the Supertram network have undergone many changes over time, with some being cancelled and others running over budget and suffering from delays in their implementation.\n\nIn May 2003 the [[South Yorkshire Passenger Transport Executive|South Yorkshire Passenger Transport Authority]] announced plans to extend the Supertram network to [[Hellaby]], a suburb of [[Rotherham]], [[Dore]], a suburb of Sheffield and [[Ranmoor]], Sheffield. So far, in February 2020 none of these extensions, estimated (in 2003) to cost a total of \u00a3400&nbsp;million has been built.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/south_yorkshire/3011725.stm|title=Supertram extension plans revealed|last=|first=|date=8 May 2003|work=|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/mobile/england/bradford/7303727.stm|title=Tram-trains to get first UK trial|last=|first=|date=18 March 2008|work=|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2008 plans were announced for the trial of [[Hybrid vehicle|diesel-electro hybrid tram trains]] on a route via [[Network Rail]] tracks to [[Huddersfield railway station|Huddersfield]] via [[Meadowhall Interchange|Meadowhall]], [[Barnsley Interchange|Barnsley]] and [[Penistone railway station|Penistone]]. The fleet of five tram trains, costing \u00a39&nbsp;million was expected to be in operation by the end of 2010 with the whole project costing \u00a324&nbsp;million for the 37 mile route. It was planned that the hourly [[Northern Rail (Serco-Abellio)|Northern Rail]] service from Barnsley to Huddersfield would be scrapped, being replaced by a more frequent tram service with more stops and a faster service due to the trams' more rapid acceleration. Plans were also announced for a second trial between [[Rotherham Central railway station|Rotherham Central]] and Sheffield at the same time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.railnews.co.uk/news/2008/08/05-northern-rail-tram-train.html|title=Penistone line is chosen for \u00a324m tram trains trial|last=|first=|date=5 August 2008|website=Rail News|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2009 plans for the Sheffield to Huddersfield route were abandoned.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/single-view/view/rotherham-tram-train-replaces-penistone-scheme.html|title=Rotherham tram-train replaces Penistone scheme|last=UK|first=DVV Media|date=|work=Railway Gazette International|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref> The Sheffield to Rotherham route was to go ahead, with trams using a Network Rail freight line. The initial plan was to use electric vehicles capable of operating on either 750\u00a0V DC or 25\u00a0kV AC. Trams are planned to go via Rotherham Central to a new station at Rotherham Parkgate. The scheme was estimated to require \u00a315&nbsp;million, later revised upwards to \u00a318.7&nbsp;million to build when first proposed, but was eventually expected to cost \u00a375.1m. The proposed route was to have been in operation by 2015, later put back until October 2018 after a series of delays.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-south-yorkshire-34473670|title=Tram-train scheme delayed by year|last=|first=|date=8 October 2015|work=BBC News|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-south-yorkshire-36315711|title=Further delays for tram-train pilot|date=18 May 2016|work=BBC News|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-south-yorkshire-40482427|title=Tram-train scheme costs spiral to \u00a375m|date=4 July 2017|work=BBC News|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref> Part of the delay was due to the transport secretary failing to approve the building of a 150m (164yd) section of track at [[Tinsley, South Yorkshire|Tinsley]] in a timely manner.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/mobile/england/south_yorkshire/8257652.stm|title=City tram-trains trial unveiled|date=15 September 2009|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref> The [[Public Accounts Committee (United Kingdom)|Public Accounts Committee]] (PAC) was critical of Network Rail's initial estimates for the cost of modifications to the route calling them, \"wholly unrealistic\". The PAC also noted that Network Rail and the [[Department for Transport]] could not provide figures on how much money had been spent on a now cancelled [[Railway electrification system|line electrification]] project.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-south-yorkshire-42354784|title=Tram-train pilot failings anger MPs|last=|first=|date=15 December 2017|work=BBC News|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rothbiz.co.uk/2017/12/news-5830-sheffield-rotherham-tram.html|title=News: Sheffield-Rotherham tram-train pilot - \"how not to run a rail project\"|last=|first=|date=|website=Rothbiz.co.uk|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref> Part of the unexpected rise in the cost of creating the route and the delay was due to the need to demolish and rebuild the College Road road over-bridge next to Rotherham Central station. It was thought that the [[Track ballast|ballast]] beneath the railway line could have been excavated to provide headroom for the [[Overhead line|catenary]] but this proved not to be feasible.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rotherhamadvertiser.co.uk/news/view,tram-works-mean-fourmonth-closure-for-town-centre-road_22268.htm|title=Tram works mean four-month closure for town centre road|last=Upton|first=Michael|date=13 April 2017|work=Rotherham Advertiser|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rothbiz.co.uk/2014/06/news-4190-preparations-for-tram-train.html|title=News: Preparations for tram train|last=|first=|date=|website=Rothbiz.co.uk|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 the [[Sheffield City Region]] invited public consultation on ''The Sheffield City Region Transport Strategy 2018-2040'' policy document (draft for consultation November 2017) in which it was revealed that only 1% of the population used the Supertram network on journeys to work in 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sheffieldcityregion.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/SCR-Transport-Strategy-Consultation-Draft.pdf|title=The Sheffield City Region Transport Strategy 2018-2040 (draft - for consultation November 2017)|last=|first=|date=November 2017|website=|page=22|accessdate=9 January 2017}}</ref>\nThe number of passengers on the Supertram network increased from 2&nbsp;million in the 1994/1995 financial years to over 12&nbsp;million in the 2016/2017 financial years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sheffieldcityregion.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/SCR-Transport-Strategy-Consultation-Draft.pdf|title=The Sheffield City Region Transport Strategy 2018-2040 (draft - for consultation November 2017)|last=|first=|date=November 2017|website=|page=25|accessdate=9 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe [[tram-train]] extension to [[Rotherham]] opened on 25 October 2018, with a fleet of seven [[Vossloh]] Citylink [[British Rail Class 399|Class 399]] tram-trains. This involves trams operating on [[Network Rail]]'s line from Tinsley to [[Rotherham Central railway station|Rotherham station]] with a short extension to Rotherham Parkgate Shopping Centre, after travelling on the Supertram line from Sheffield Cathedral to Meadowhall South/Tinsley.<ref>[http://www.railwaygazette.com/nc/news/single-view/view/rotherham-tram-tram-project-funding-confirmed.html Rotherham tram-tram project funding confirmed] ''Railway Gazette International'' 17 May 2012</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestar.co.uk/news/business/business-news/new-2017-hope-for-delayed-60m-sheffield-to-rotherham-tram-train-scheme-1-7005138|title=New 2017 hope for delayed \u00a360m Sheffield to Rotherham tram-train scheme|publisher=The Star|accessdate=27 March 2015}}</ref> The station at Rotherham Central is a combined tram stop and [[railway station]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rotherhamadvertiser.co.uk/news/100942/pioneering-tram-train-on-track-for-rotherham-launch.aspx|title=Pioneering tram train on track for Rotherham launch|last=|first=|date=|work=Rotherham Advertiser|accessdate=9 January 2018}}</ref> To cater for the tram train services, platforms 1 and 2 at Rotherham Central were extended, with the extensions being numbered platforms 3 and 4 respectively. The stop at Parkgate is a single platform terminus.\n\n==Accidents and incidents==\n\n* In 1995, engineer William Roe suffered severe [[brain damage]] after his car skidded on wet tram tracks and crashed into a metal pole. Supertram were made to award Mr Roe compensation for failing to ensure that the rails were level with the adjacent road surface, and for the lack of warning signs indicating that the tracks are hazardous when wet. It was reported there were 53 accidents involving Supertram in Sheffield between 1994 and 1997, including two fatalities and 12 serious injuries.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1360466/Tram-firms-face-big-claims-after-crash-case.html|title=Tram firms face big claims after crash case|first=Paul |last=Stokes|date=25 October 2001|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=27 November 2014}}</ref> \n* On 7 March 2003, a man died from serious head injuries after he was hit by a tram whilst lying on the tracks.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/2832199.stm|title=Man dies in Supertram accident |work=BBC News |date=8 March 2003 |accessdate=27 November 2014}}</ref>\n* On 27 October 2005, a pedestrian was killed after stepping in front of an approaching tram.<ref>[http://www.raib.gov.uk/cms_resources.cfm?file=/060301_R012006_StaniforthRoad.pdf \"Tram, Pedestrian Collision at Staniforth Road, Sheffield, 27 October 2005.\"] ''Rail Accident Investigation Branch'', March 2006.</ref>\n* On 20 September 2008, a 75-year-old woman was seriously injured when she was fell and was subsequently struck by a tram while it was arriving at the local tram stop.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/south_yorkshire/7626738.stm|website=BBC News|title=Woman badly hurt in tram accident|date=20 September 2008}}</ref> The woman was removed and transferred to the [[Northern General Hospital]], suffering from head injuries and a fractured pelvis leg.\n* On 22 October 2015, trams 120 and 118 collided at Shalesmoor. This resulted in the two damaged sections of both trams requiring major repairs, whilst the undamaged parts of trams 120 and 118 were put together and painted in a version of the original Sheffield Tramways cream and blue livery to re-create the original 120. Tram 118 returned to service a year later in October 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.britishtramsonline.co.uk/news/?p=15771 |title=In Pictures: Stagecoach Supertram 118\u2019s revised look |date=15 November 2016 |work=British Trams Online |accessdate=6 June 2017}}</ref>\n* In November 2016, teacher Terry Orwin sustained serious head injuries from crashing while riding a bicycle on Langsett Road and being caught by the tram tracks.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thestar.co.uk/news/helmet-saves-sheffield-dad-after-horror-bike-crash-1-8241727 |title=Helmet saves Sheffield dad after horror bike crash |date=16 November 2016 |work=Sheffield Star |accessdate=9 February 2017}}</ref>\n* In December 2016, Saleh Qassim Saleh, 81, was killed in collision with a tram. The driver was charged with causing death by careless driving.<ref>[https://www.thestar.co.uk/news/woman-appears-at-court-charged-over-sheffield-tram-crash-that-killed-pensioner-1-9499447 \"Woman appears at court charged over Sheffield tram crash that killed pensioner\"], ''Sheffield Star'', 18 December 2018.</ref>\n* In June 2017, two trams were involved in a low-speed collision at Halfway.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.co.uk/news/breaking-sheffield-tram-crash-causing-havoc-on-public-transport-network-1-8585134|title=BREAKING: Sheffield tram crash causing havoc on public transport network|accessdate=2 August 2018}}</ref>\n* In July 2018 a passenger was injured when they were thrown across the tram as a result tram overspeeding at Middlewood Road and then braking suddenly. The impact of the passenger with a door caused the door to open.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/passenger-injury-following-tram-overspeeding-at-middlewood-road|title=Passenger injury following tram overspeeding at Middlewood Road|work=GOV.UK|accessdate=2 August 2018}}</ref>\n* On 25 October 2018, the day the Tram-Train service launched, a lorry collided with one such tram at approximately 3.30&nbsp;pm on Staniforth Road, near the Woodbourn Road station, derailing the tram-train. Three people were injured with two being treated on site and one taken to hospital.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-south-yorkshire-45976460|title=Tram-train crashes on first day of service|date=25 October 2018|work=BBC News|accessdate=25 October 2018}}</ref> Initial reports indicate that the lorry pulled across the path of the Tram.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/calendar/2018-10-25/lorry-hits-sheffield-tram/|title=Lorry collides with Sheffield tram-train on first day of new service|publisher=|work=ITV News|accessdate=25 October 2018}}</ref> On 12 August 2019, lorry driver Kevin Hague, 61, of Rotherham admitted driving through a red light at Sheffield Magistrates' Court. The BBC reported, 'In a personal impact statement read to the court the driver of the tram-train said he was thankful he was in one of the new \u00a34m vehicles. They are built to higher crash-worthiness standards as they also run on Network Rail tracks.'<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-south-yorkshire-49319941|title=Lorry driver fined over tram-train crash|last=|first=|date=12 August 2019|work=BBC News|access-date=12 August 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n* On 30 November 2018, a car collided with a tram-train at approximately 4.30 pm on Staniforth Road.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-south-yorkshire-46407052|title=Three injured as tram and car collide in Sheffield|publisher=|work=BBC News|accessdate=30 November 2018}}</ref>\n* On 22 May 2019, a man was hit by a tram shortly after having an argument with two men.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-south-yorkshire-48381290|title=Man seriously injured by Sheffield tram after argument|publisher=|work=BBC News|accessdate=26 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Man suffers serious injuries after being hit by tram in Sheffield |url=http://www.britishtramsonline.co.uk/news/?p=27783 |website=British Trams Online |accessdate=26 May 2019}}</ref> He later died on 26 May 2019 and was named as Martin Rigg.<ref>{{cite web |title=Man hit by tram in Sheffield dies in hospital |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-south-yorkshire-48413602 |website=BBC News |accessdate=26 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Sheffield tram death man named as Martin Rigg |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-south-yorkshire-48432084 |website=BBC News |accessdate=6 June 2019}}</ref> A man was arrested on suspicion of murder on 1 June 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Murder arrest over Martin Rigg Sheffield tram death |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-south-yorkshire-48483685 |website=BBC News |accessdate=6 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Sheffield Tramway]] \u2013 the original Sheffield tramway system.\n* [[Light Rail Transit Association]]\n* [[List of town tramway systems in England]]\n* [[List of town tramway systems in the United Kingdom]]\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{notelist-lr}}\n;Citations\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Sheffield Supertram}}\n{{Attached KML|display=title,inline}}\n* [http://www.supertram.com/ Supertram website]\n* [http://www.thetrams.co.uk/supertram/ Stagecoach Supertram at thetrams.co.uk]\n* [http://bbs.keyhole.com/ubb/showthreaded.php/Cat/0/Number/240058 Collection of Google Earth locations of Stagecoach Supertram stops] (Requires [http://earth.google.com Google Earth software]) from the Google Earth Community forum.\n* [http://www.supertram.com/uploads/vehicleinfo.pdf Supertram specs]\n\n{{Stagecoach Sheffield Supertram}}\n{{UK light rail}}\n{{Britishmetros}}\n{{StagecoachGroup}}\n\n[[Category:Stagecoach Group rail services]]\n[[Category:Sheffield Supertram| ]]\n[[Category:Railway lines opened in 1994]]\n[[Category:1994 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Light rail in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Tram transport in England]]\n[[Category:750 V DC railway electrification]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Light rail tramway in Sheffield, England}}\n{{About|a tramway opened in 1994|trams operating 1873\u20131960|Sheffield Tramway}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2018}}\n{{Use British English|date=January 2018}}\n{{Infobox Public transit\n| name                        = Sheffield Supertram\n| image                       = StagecoachSuperT.svg\n| image2                      = Sheffield supertram at Cathedral stop - DSC07446.JPG\n| caption2                    = A [[Siemens-Duewag Supertram|Siemens-Duewag ''Supertram'']], operating a service to Halfway, seen in July 2010.\n| locale                      = [[South Yorkshire]]\n| area served                 = {{plainlist|\n* [[Rotherham]]\n* [[Sheffield]]\n}}\n| transit_type                = {{plainlist|\n* [[Light rail]]\n* [[Tram]]\n* [[Tram-train]]\n}}\n| lines                       = 4\n| stations                    = 50\n| ridership                   = \n| annual_ridership            = 11.9 million (2018/19)<ref name=\"2018/19DfTstats\">{{cite web |title=Light Rail and Tram Statistics, England: 2018/19 |url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/809894/light-rail-and-tram-statistics-england-2019.pdf |publisher=[[Department for Transport]] |accessdate=19 June 2019}}</ref><br>{{decrease}} 3.1%\n| headquarters                = Nunnery Depot<br> Woodbourn Road<br> [[Sheffield]]<br> S9 3LS\n| began_operation             = 21 March 1994<br>({{Years or months ago|1994|3}})\n| owner                       = [[South Yorkshire Passenger Transport Executive]]\n| operator                    = [[Stagecoach Group|Stagecoach]]\n| chief_executive             = Tim Bilby\n| vehicles                    = {{plainlist|\n* 25 [[Siemens-Duewag Supertram|Siemens-Duewag ''Supertram'']]\n* 7 [[British Rail Class 399|Class 399]] [[Stadler Citylink|Stadler ''Citylink'']]\n}}\n| system_length               = {{convert|34.6|km|mi|abbr=on}}\n| track_gauge                 = {{RailGauge|1435mm|al=on}}\n| el                          = [[Overhead line]]<br>(750 [[Volt|V]] [[Direct current|DC]])\n| minimum_radius_of_curvature = \n| top_speed                   = {{cvt|55|mph|kph|abbr=on}}\n| map_name                    = \n| map                         = \n| map_state                   = collapsed\n| website                     = {{url|https://www.stagecoachbus.com/supertram}}\n| imagesize                   = \n| alt                         = \n| caption                     = \n| line_number                 = \n| start                       = \n| end                         = \n| character                   = \n}}\n\nThe '''Sheffield Supertram''' (or '''Stagecoach Supertram''') is a [[light rail]] [[tram]] network, covering [[Sheffield]] and [[Rotherham]]. Infrastructure is owned by the [[South Yorkshire Passenger Transport Executive]] (SYPTE), with operator [[Stagecoach Group|Stagecoach]] responsible for the operation and maintenance of rolling stock.\n\nInterest in the development of a modern tram system for Sheffield mounted during the 1980s, after further planning was performed by SYPTE, the Supertram proposal was approved via an [[Act of Parliament#United Kingdom Parliament|Act of Parliament]] during 1991. Construction of the Supertram network, which incorporated several existing heavy rail sections as well as new track, was carried out in sections, allowing for the commencement of the first revenue services during 1994. Early operations were hindered by a complex ticketing system and the initially small coverage area, contributing to disappointing ridership figures during its first years.<ref name = \"rail mag15\">[https://www.railmagazine.com/infrastructure/light-rail/sheffield-supertram-s-logical-progression \"Sheffield Supertram\u2019s logical progression\"] ''[[Rail (magazine)|Rail]]'' 9 December 2015</ref>\n\nDuring 1997, in an efforts to turn around the network's performance, the operation of Supertram was privatised to Stagecoach at price of \u00a31.15 million, who took over from South Yorkshire Supertram Limited. Following management and operational changes, as well as further expansion of the system, ridership numbers have risen considerably.<ref name = \"rail mag15\"/> The Supertram network currently consists of 50 stations across four colour-coded lines, the '''Blue''', '''Purple''', '''Yellow''' and '''Tram-Train''' ('''Black''') routes. As well as connecting with local and national bus and rail services, the network serves six [[park and ride]] sites.<ref>[https://www.stagecoachbus.com/supertram/about-supertraml About Supertram]{{Dead link|date=January 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }} 'Stagecoach Supertram'</ref>\n\nStarting in 2008, interest has been expressed in the launch of hybrid [[tram-train]] operations, enabling services to traverse sections of the main line rail network in addition to tramways. During 2012, this interest solidified into an experimental trial being planned, as this would be the first deployment of tram-trains anywhere in the United Kingdom. The start of tram-train operations, using a purpose-procured fleet of new [[Vossloh]]-built [[British Rail Class 399|Class 399]] [[Vossloh Citylink|Citylink]] [[electric multiple unit]]s, had been repeatedly delayed due to shortcomings in the planning of infrastructure adaptations, while significant cost overruns have also been experienced. On 25 October 2018, Supertram commenced operations of the new tram-train line from Cathedral to [[Rotherham Parkgate tram stop|Rotherham Parkgate]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stagecoachbus.com/supertram/tram-train/introducing-tram-train|title=Supertram {{!}} Tram Train|website=www.stagecoachbus.com|accessdate=21 October 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181021151151/https://www.stagecoachbus.com/supertram/tram-train/introducing-tram-train|archivedate=21 October 2018|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n===Initial development===\nThe origins of what would become the Supertram network came from within the ambitions that were held by the South Yorkshire Passenger Transport Executive (SYPTE), which was initially a constituent element of the short-lived (1974\u20131986) [[South Yorkshire County Council]], being assigned the role of public transport coordination.<ref name = \"rail tech\"/> Akin to many the larger British cities, [[Sheffield]] had once possessed an extensive tram network, the [[Sheffield Tramway]], which had been completely closed by the end of 1960 amid arguments that motorised [[bus]]es offered superior economics to trams.<ref name = \"rail mag15\"/> The SYPTE took interest in an earlier and more expansive light rail proposal, deciding to investigate it further. The original plan was refined and sufficiently modified to include multiple pre-existing heavy rail alignments in advance of efforts being made to secure the required permissions to proceed.<ref name = \"rail tech\">[https://www.railway-technology.com/projects/sheffield-tram/ \"Sheffield Supertram, Operated by Stagecoach Supertram, United Kingdom.\"] ''railway-technology.com'', Retrieved: 12 May 2018.</ref>\n\nDuring 1985, an [[Act of Parliament#United Kingdom Parliament|Act of Parliament]] authorised the construction of the Supertram. The initial line, on which construction commenced during 1991, was built by the SYPTE at a cost of \u00a3240&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.bbc.co.uk/southyorkshire/content/articles/2005/10/06/sheffield_supertram_feature.shtml |title = Sheffield Supertram information |work = BBC South Yorkshire |publisher = BBC News |accessdate = 11 March 2009}}</ref><ref name=\"thetrams_history\" /> Between 1994 and 1995, the first line was opened in several stages; the first section to open, which was located along a former heavy rail alignment to [[Meadowhall Interchange|Meadowhall]], was opened on 21 March 1994.<ref name=\"thetrams_history\" /> The start of services on the Supertram came only shortly after the launch of another modern tram network, the [[Manchester Metrolink]] network.\n\nUpon opening, the network was operated by South Yorkshire Supertram Limited,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://data.companieshouse.gov.uk/doc/company/02634683|title=SOUTH YORKSHIRE SUPERTRAM LIMITED|website=data.companieshouse.gov.uk|accessdate=25 October 2018}}</ref> which was an originally wholly owned subsidiary company of SYPTE established to run the venture. The early years of the Supertram were not straightforward; in the eyes of some officials, the scheme was reportedly viewed as having been a failure. Running in direct competition with cheaper and more frequent [[bus]]es, far greater numbers of passengers chose to continue commuting by means other than the fledgling tram network; retailers also frequently complained due to the disruption caused by the lengthy construction works performed while establishing the Supertram network.<ref name = \"20year bbc\">Vincent, James. [https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-south-yorkshire-26663137 \"Sheffield Supertram marks 20-year journey\"] ''BBC News'' 21 March 2014</ref> The complex ticketing system originally adopted has also been attributed as having being a source of irritance and confusion to would-be passengers.<ref name = \"rail mag15\"/>\n\nWithin the first two years of operations, it became clear that the projections for passenger numbers had been overly optimistic, while there was concern that the system represented poor value for money and did not seem to be gaining traction.<ref name = \"20year bbc\"/> Thus, the issue of what party should bear the cost became a politicised matter. Allegedly, by 1996, the councils backing the Supertram had recognised that the operation had both operational and managerial problems which required addressing, thus consultants were asked to draw up options for the system's reorganisation into a more commercially viable venture, including the [[Passenger rail franchising in Great Britain|franchising]] of Supertram and its wholesale selling-off.<ref name = \"rail mag15\"/>\n\n===Privatisation===\n[[File:Sheffield Supertram - Meadowhall Interchange_07-07-04.jpg|thumb|Two [[Siemens-Duewag Supertram]]s at [[Meadowhall Interchange]] in July 2004 in a modified version of the original Stagecoach livery]]\n[[File:Supertram 104 at Gleadless Townend tramstop Sheffield.jpg|thumb|[[Siemens-Duewag Supertram]] 124 arriving at Gleadless Townend tram stop, on the Blue Route to Halfway]]\n\nDuring December 1997, the operating company, South Yorkshire Supertram Limited, was [[Privatisation|privatised]], having been sold to the international transportation company [[Stagecoach Group|Stagecoach]] for \u00a31.15&nbsp;million; the sale left multiple local councils with the long-term debt for the Supertram's establishment however.<ref>[https://www.independent.co.uk/news/sheffield-supertram-falls-victim-to-competition-from-cheap-buses-1336364.html \"Sheffield supertram falls victim to competition from cheap buses.\"] ''[[The Independent]]'', 10 June 1996.</ref> The sale price was substantially below the anticipated \u00a380 million that the councils had hoped to raise to help pay off the accumulated debts from the system.<ref>[http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/uk/3651587.stm \"Losses 'jeopardising tram plans'.\"] ''BBC News'', 23 April 2005.</ref> Under the terms of the deal struck by the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] government of the era, a measurable reduction in the system's operating costs was achieved, but it had also meant that the people of South Yorkshire were each paying 5p per week for the Supertram, a practice which was continued over many years.<ref name = \"20year bbc\"/> Stagecoach acquired the concession for the maintenance and operation of the Supertram network until 2024.<ref name=thetrams_history>{{cite web |last= Courtenay |first=Peter |url=http://www.thetrams.co.uk/supertram/history.php |title=Sheffield Supertram: History |accessdate=19 August 2007 |work=TheTrams.co.uk }}</ref><ref name = \"20year bbc\"/>\n\nWhile there were initially plans for Supertram extend service coverage to a greater area of South Yorkshire, such as via envisioned lines that would have run to [[Barnsley]] and [[Doncaster]], progress on such ambitions has been restricted.<ref name = \"20year bbc\"/> According to ''[[BBC News]]'', there has been considerable frustration expressed amongst people outside of Sheffield that they are essentially paying for something they do not use. However, as of 2014, plans to extend Supertram are in various stages of action, and the network has been extended as time has gone on.<ref name = \"20year bbc\"/> Over time, patronage of the Supertram has typically gone up, having grown from 7.8&nbsp;million passenger journeys in 1996/97, to 15.0&nbsp;million during 2011/12.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/light-rail-and-tram-statistics-2011-12 | title=Light rail and tram statistics: 2011/12 | publisher=Government Digital Service | date=19 July 2012}} Table LRT0101.</ref><ref name = \"20year bbc\"/>\n\nThe substantial increase in the Supertram's usage over the years has been credited to various factors. Industry publication ''[[Rail (magazine)|Rail]]'' has pointed towards changes to route patterns, the introduction of onboard conductors, ticket simplification and refurbishment of the trams themselves having generated greater appeal amongst the travelling public.<ref name = \"rail mag15\"/> Between 2011 and 2017, both the number of passengers and operating revenue have declined; during 2016/17, the network carried 12.6 million passengers.<ref name=\"16/17DfTstats\">{{cite web |title=Light Rail and Tram Statistics: England 2016/17 |url=https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/623366/light-rail-tram-ending-march-2017.pdf |publisher=Department for Transport |accessdate=30 June 2017}}</ref> Reasons presented for the reduction in commuter usage have included the disruptive wide-scale rail replacement effort across the Supertram network, which involved partial closures and the use of buses as temporary tram replacements, as well as the impact of cheaper [[petrol]].<ref name = \"rail mag15\"/><ref>[https://www.railpro.co.uk/railpro-magazine/april-2017/interview-margaret-kay \"Interview: Margaret Key.\"] ''Rail Professional'', 29 March 2017.</ref>\n\n==Current network==\n===Overview===\nThe Sheffield Supertram network is organised around [[Park Square, Sheffield|Park Square]] and comprises four lines. The lines, with termini at [[Meadowhall Interchange]], [[Rotherham Parkgate tram stop|Rotherham Parkgate]], Halfway and [[Hillsborough, South Yorkshire|Hillsborough]], all serve Sheffield city centre and meet at Park Square where a triangular junction was constructed to provide interchange between lines and operational flexibility. A pair of small branches serving Malin Bridge, from [[Hillsborough Interchange]], and [[Herdings Park]] branch out from two of the main lines.<ref name = \"rail mag15\"/>\n\nThe Sheffield Supertram runs from [[Sheffield City Centre]] north-west to [[Middlewood, Sheffield|Middlewood]] and [[Malin Bridge]] via the [[University of Sheffield]] and [[Hillsborough, England|Hillsborough]]; north-east to [[Meadowhall Interchange]] and Rotherham Parkgate via [[Attercliffe]]; and south-east to [[Mosborough|Halfway]] and Herdings Park via [[Norfolk Park]], [[Manor, Sheffield|Manor]], and [[Gleadless]]. The three main [[Sheffield City Centre|City Centre]] stops are located on one side of a former [[dual carriageway]], now a single lane and reserved for buses and taxis only. These three stops are served by all routes.{{citation needed|date=February 2020}}\n\n[[File:SheffieldSupertramMap.svg|center|thumb|605px|A map of the Supertram network. [[Template:Sheffield Supertram|Diagram of the Supertram network]]]]\n\n===Frequencies===\nThe off-peak daytime frequencies are:\n*Yellow Line - 12 minutes\n*Blue Line - 12 minutes\n*Purple Line - 30 minutes\n*Tram Train - 20 minutes\n\nA reduced level of service was introduced across the Supertram network on 23 March 2020, in response to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom]]. A modified Sunday timetable will operate on all days.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stagecoachbus.com/news/yorkshire/2020/march/revised-tram-timetables-from-monday-23-march-2020|website=Stagecoach Supertram|date=19 March 2020|title=Revised Tram Timetables from Monday 23 March 2020|accessdate=27 March 2020}}</ref> Services were further reduced on 1 April.\n\n===Tram-train services===\n{{Infobox Rail companies\n|name           = Supertram\n|logo_filename  = \n|image_filename = \n|image_size     = 300px\n|franchise      = Tram-train operator, not subject to franchising\n|nameforarea    = Region\n|regions        = [[South Yorkshire]]\n|secregions     = [[North East Derbyshire]]\n|fleet          = 32\n|abbr           = \n|stations       = 50\n|stationsop     = \n|passkm0708     = \n|routekm        = 29\n|parent_company = [[Stagecoach Group|Stagecoach]]\n}}\n\nSupertram began operations of the new (in 2018) tram-train line from Cathedral to Rotherham Parkgate, using seven brand new [[Vossloh]]-built [[British Rail Class 399|Class 399]] ''Citylink'' articulated [[electric multiple unit]]s.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rotherham.gov.uk/news/article/659/uks_first_tram_train_unveiled_in_south_yorkshire|title=UK's First Tram Train Unveiled in South Yorkshire|last=Davis|first=Ceri|date=10 December 2015|website=Rotherham.gov.uk|accessdate=9 January 2018}}</ref> The existing [[Siemens-Duewag Supertram]] fleet were not upgraded for tram-train operation, so have not been registered under [[TOPS]] and cannot be used on the line as they lack the relevant [[Network Rail]] safety systems and [[crashworthiness]]. The tram-train scheme was first planned to be in service by 2015 but was delayed.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-south-yorkshire-34473670|title=Sheffield to Rotherham tram-train scheme delayed by year|date=8 October 2015|newspaper=BBC News|accessdate=26 November 2016}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-south-yorkshire-38103252|title=Sheffield to Rotherham tram-train scheme delayed further|date=25 November 2016|newspaper=BBC News|accessdate=26 November 2016}}</ref> The first test run (as far as Magna) was performed in the early hours of 10 May 2018 and the first gauging run all the way to Parkgate occurred in the early hours of 5 June 2018.<ref>[https://www.metro-report.com/news/projects/single-view/view/sheffield-tram-train-runs-onto-network-rail-infrastructure.html Sheffield tram-train runs onto Network Rail infrastructure] ''[[Metro Report International]]'' 14 May 2018</ref> It opened on 25 October 2018.<ref>[https://www.metro-report.com/news/light-rail/single-view/view/rotherham-tram-train-to-launch-this-month.html Rotherham tram-train to launch this month] ''Metro Report International'' 4 October 2018</ref> However it was suspended later in the day due to a crash.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-south-yorkshire-45976460|title=Tram-train crashes on first day of service|date=25 October 2018|publisher=|accessdate=25 October 2018|work=BBC News}}</ref>\n\nThe Class 399 units were built in 2015/16 with the first delivered in December 2015.<ref name=RGI201115>[http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/news/europe/single-view/view/first-tram-train-heads-for-sheffield.html First tram-train heads for Sheffield] ''[[Railway Gazette International]]'' 20 November 2015</ref> Until the completion of the tram-train line, some were used to provide increased capacity on the existing Supertram network. They first entered service on 17 September 2017.<ref>[http://www.stagecoach.com/media/news-releases/2017/2017-09-14.aspx Minister launches first Citylink tram train into service] Stagecoach 14 September 2017</ref><ref>[http://www.metro-report.com/news/light-rail/single-view/view/sheffield-tram-train-enters-service.html Sheffield tram-train enters service] ''Metro Report International'' 15 September 2017</ref> On 9 April 2019 a fault was found on the Class 399 units and they were withdrawn to undergo safety checks. Tram-train service was suspended<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-south-yorkshire-47879898|title=Tram-trains suspended after fault found|last=|first=|date=10 April 2019|work=BBC News|accessdate=14 April 2019}}</ref> and resumed during the next day.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thestar.co.uk/news/traffic-and-travel/fault-found-on-sheffield-to-rotherham-tram-train-service-1-9703649|title=Fault found on Sheffield to Rotherham tram-train service|last=|first=|date=10 April 2019|work=Sheffield Star|accessdate=5 May 2019}}</ref> The tram-train service was suspended again on 14 December 2019,<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-south-yorkshire-50794010|title=Tram-trains suspended 'on maker's advice'|last=|first=|date=14 December 2019|work=BBC News|access-date=14 December 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref> but resumed on 17 December 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=ST Tram Train Service Update |url=https://www.stagecoachbus.com/news/yorkshire/2019/december/tram-train-service-update |website=www.stagecoachbus.com |accessdate=20 December 2019 |language=en |date=17 December 2019}}</ref>\n\n===SupertramLink bus services===\n\n[[Stagecoach Sheffield]] operate the SL1 and SL1a \"SupertramLink\" routes between the Middlewood terminus of the yellow route and [[Stocksbridge]], via [[Oughtibridge]]. The bus runs at the same frequency as the tram and is timetabled to connect with the tram at Middlewood, to provide additional journey opportunities. Through single, return, day and week tickets are available to allow travel on both Supertram and SupertramLink bus services.\n\n===Tram stops===\n{| class=\"toccolours\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse;\" cellspacing=\"2\" cellpadding=\"4\" border=\"1\"\n! style=\"background: #{{Sheffield Supertram colour|Yellow Line}}; color: white;\" width=\"25%\" | Yellow Route\n! style=\"background: #{{Sheffield Supertram colour|Blue Line}}; color: white;\" width=\"25%\" | Blue Route\n! style=\"background: #{{Sheffield Supertram colour|Purple Line}}; color: white;\" width=\"25%\" | Purple Route\n! style=\"background: #000000; color: white;\" width=\"25%\" | ''Tram-train\n|-\n\n<!-- Yellow Route -->\n| valign=\"top\" |\n* [[Middlewood, Sheffield|Middlewood]]\n* Leppings Lane\n* [[Hillsborough Park]]\n* [[Hillsborough Interchange]] {{rail-interchange|bus}}\n* Bamforth Street\n* Langsett Primrose View\n* Infirmary Road\n* Shalesmoor\n* [[Netherthorpe, Sheffield#Modern developments|Netherthorpe Road]]\n* [[University of Sheffield]]\n* [[West End, Sheffield|West Street]]\n* [[Sheffield City Hall|City Hall]]\n* [[Sheffield Cathedral|Cathedral]]\n* [[Castle Square, Sheffield|Castle Square]]\n* [[Fitzalan Square]] {{rail-interchange|bus}}\n* [[Hyde Park, South Yorkshire|Hyde Park]]\n* Cricket Inn Road\n* Nunnery Square\n* Woodbourn Road\n* [[Attercliffe]]\n* [[Sheffield Arena|Arena]]/[[Olympic Legacy Park]]\n* [[Valley Centertainment]]\n* [[Carbrook, South Yorkshire|Carbrook]]\n* [[Darnall#Tinsley|Tinsley]] [[Darnall#Meadowhall|Meadowhall South]]\n* [[Meadowhall Interchange]] {{rail-interchange|gb|rail}} {{rail-interchange|bus}}\n\n<!-- Blue Route -->\n| valign=\"top\" |\n* [[Malin Bridge]]\n* [[Hillsborough Interchange]] {{rail-interchange|bus}}\n* Bamforth Street\n* Langsett Primrose View\n* Infirmary Road\n* Shalesmoor\n* [[Netherthorpe, Sheffield#Modern developments|Netherthorpe Road]]\n* [[University of Sheffield]]\n* [[West End, Sheffield|West Street]]\n* [[Sheffield City Hall|City Hall]]\n* [[Sheffield Cathedral|Cathedral]]\n* [[Castle Square, Sheffield|Castle Square]]\n* [[Fitzalan Square]] {{rail-interchange|bus}}\n* [[Sheffield station#Supertram stop|Sheffield Station / Sheffield Hallam University]] {{rail-interchange|gb|rail}}\n* Granville Road / The [[Sheffield College]]\n* Park Grange Croft\n* [[Norfolk Park|Park Grange Road]]\n* Arbourthorne Road\n* Spring Lane\n* [[Manor, South Yorkshire|Manor Top]]\n* Hollinsend\n* [[Gleadless Townend]]\n* White Lane\n* [[Birley]] Lane\n* Birley Moor Road\n* [[Hackenthorpe]]\n* Donetsk Way\n* Moss Way\n* [[Crystal Peaks]] {{rail-interchange|bus}}\n* [[Beighton, Sheffield|Beighton]] Drake House Lane\n* [[Waterthorpe]]\n* [[Westfield, South Yorkshire|Westfield]]\n* [[Mosborough#Halfway|Halfway]]\n\n<!-- [[Stagecoach Supertram Purple Line|Purple Line]] -->\n| valign=\"top\" |\n* [[Herdings Park#Herdings|Herdings Park]]\n* Herdings Leighton Road\n* [[Gleadless Townend]]\n* Hollinsend\n* [[Manor, South Yorkshire|Manor Top]]\n* Spring Lane\n* Arbourthorne Road\n* [[Norfolk Park|Park Grange Road]]\n* Park Grange Croft\n* Granville Road / The [[Sheffield College]]\n* [[Sheffield station#Supertram stop|Sheffield Station / Sheffield Hallam University]] {{rail-interchange|gb|rail}}\n* [[Fitzalan Square]] {{rail-interchange|bus}}\n* [[Castle Square, Sheffield|Castle Square]]\n* [[Sheffield Cathedral|Cathedral]]\n\n<!-- ''Tram-train'' -->\n| valign=\"top\" |\n* [[Parkgate, South Yorkshire|Rotherham Parkgate]]\n* [[Rotherham Central railway station|Rotherham Central]] {{rail-interchange|gb|rail}} {{rail-interchange|bus}}\n* [[Darnall#Tinsley|Tinsley]] / [[Darnall#Meadowhall|Meadowhall South]]\n* [[Carbrook, South Yorkshire|Carbrook]]\n* [[Valley Centertainment]]\n* [[Sheffield Arena|Arena]] / [[Olympic Legacy Park]]\n* [[Attercliffe]]\n* Woodbourn Road\n* Nunnery Square\n* Cricket Inn Road\n* [[Hyde Park, South Yorkshire|Hyde Park]]\n* [[Fitzalan Square]] {{rail-interchange|bus}}\n* [[Castle Square, Sheffield|Castle Square]]\n* [[Sheffield Cathedral|Cathedral]]\n|}\n\n==Rolling stock==\n===Current fleet===\nSheffield Supertram operates the following fleet:\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" |&nbsp;Class&nbsp;\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Image\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Type\n! colspan=\"2\" |&nbsp;Top speed&nbsp;\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Length<br/>metres\n! colspan=\"3\" |&nbsp;Capacity&nbsp;\n! rowspan=\"2\" |&nbsp;In<br/>service&nbsp;\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Orders\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Fleet<br/>numbers\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Routes<br/>operated\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Built\n! rowspan=\"2\" |Years<br/>operated\n|- style=\"background:#f9f9f9;\"\n!&nbsp;mph&nbsp;\n!&nbsp;km/h&nbsp;\n!<abbr title=\"Seated\">Std</abbr>\n!<abbr title=\"Standing\">Sdg</abbr>\n!Total\n|-\n|[[Siemens-Duewag Supertram]]\n|[[File:Supertram 104 at Cathedral tram stop.jpg|90px]]\n|[[Tram]]\n|50\n|80\n|34.8\n|86\n|115\n|201\n|25\n|&mdash;\n|101-125\n|Blue, Purple, Yellow\n|1992\n|1994-present\n|-\n|[[British Rail Class 399|Stadler Citylink]]<br/>(Class 399)\n|[[File:Class 399 at Cathedral tram stop.jpg|90px]]\n|[[Tram-train]]\n|62\n|100\n|37.2\n|88\n|150\n|238\n|7\n|&mdash;\n|201-207{{efn-lr|Because these vehicles operate on the National Rail network in addition to the Supertram network, they have been allocated the [[TOPS]] numbers 399201-399207}}\n|Blue, Purple, Tram-Train, Yellow\n|2014-2015\n|2017-present\n|-\n!Total\n!colspan=\"8\" |\n!32\n!&mdash;\n!colspan=\"4\" |\n|}\n\n====Siemens-Duewag Supertram====\n{{Main|Siemens-Duewag Supertram}}\nThe network operates 25 three car trams built by [[Siemens Mobility|Siemens]]-[[Duewag]] of [[D\u00fcsseldorf]], Germany, in 1992. The trams are 40% low floor design, the vehicles have been specially designed for gradients as steep as 10%. In the 1980s a design choice was taken to create the longest possible vehicle to avoid multiple working<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.supertram.com/uploads/Designingourtrams.pdf|title=Home - Supertram|website=Supertram.com|accessdate=4 August 2018}}</ref> which resulted in a {{Convert|34.8|m|adj = on}} design, the third-longest tram design in operation in Europe at the time<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.supertram.com/uploads/vehicleinfo.pdf|title=Home - Supertram|website=Supertram.com|accessdate=4 August 2018}}</ref> and the longest in service in the UK until the {{Convert|42.8|m|adj = on}} long [[Edinburgh Tram (vehicle)|Edinburgh Trams]] were introduced.\n\nLaunched in an initial light grey livery, following the awarding of the operating franchise to Stagecoach the trams were reliveried in Stagecoach's corporate livery from 1997. From 2006 the trams were refurbished, and a new dedicated Supertram blue\u2013based livery was launched, rolled out by 2008.\n\n====Stadler Citylink (Class 399)====\n{{Main|British Rail Class 399|Stadler Citylink}}\n[[Stadler Rail|Stadler]] supplied seven [[British Rail Class 399|tram-train vehicles]], delivered between November 2015 and November 2016.<ref name=RGI201115/>\n\n==Infrastructure==\n[[File:Supertram Castle Square.jpg|thumb|[[Siemens-Duewag Supertram]] 125 leaving Castle Square tram stop, on the Purple Route to [[Meadowhall Interchange]]]]\n\n===Track===\n[[File:Sheffield Supertram - Park Square 02-07-04.jpg|thumb|right|Detail of the Supertram [[triangular junction]] at Park Square]] \nThe network is {{convert|29|km|mi|abbr=on}} long, with {{convert|60|km|mi|abbr=on}} of track.<ref name=\"technical\">{{cite web |url=http://www.supertram.com/technical.html |title=About us: Technical |accessdate=19 August 2007 |work=Stagecoach Supertram}}</ref> It features two types of track; [[tramway track]] where either pedestrians or road traffic share the right of way and ballasted [[Rail tracks|railway track]] when there are no such requirements.\n\nTramway track consists of a [[Grooved rail|grooved tramway rail]] set into a concrete base with troughs into which the rails are laid. Most of the track is on-street using 35G-section grooved tram rail, with BS11-80A {{convert|80|lb/yd|kg/m|1|abbr=on}} [[flat-bottom rail]] elsewhere.<ref name=\"technical\" /> The railway track was supplied by [[British Steel Corporation]] Track Products of Workington and laid on sleepers consisting of concrete blocks with steel ties which gives a spring feeling when travelling on these sections. The track is laid on a bed of ballast which in turn rests on a prepared formation. Street crossings are usually laid with grooved tramway rails.\n\n===Overhead wiring===\nSupertram is powered through 12 electric substations and fed through {{Convert|107|mm2|adj = on|abbr = on}} cross-section [[Overhead lines|overhead line]] equipment (OHLE) wire.<ref name=\"technical\" /> The substations convert the 11&nbsp;kV&nbsp;AC supply into 750&nbsp;V&nbsp;DC supply into the overhead. The 12 substations are situated as follows:\n* Blackburn Meadows\n* Carbrook\n* Nunnery Square\n* Park Square\n* Arbourthorne\n* Gleadless Townend\n* Birley\n* Crystal Peaks, Ochre Dyke Lane\n* Halfway, Eckington Way\n* University, Brook Hill\n* Langsett Road, Capel Street\n* Middlewood\n\nThe overhead line equipment depends on the location. If the tracks are close together, central poles with 'steady' arms on each side are used. If the tracks are further apart, poles on either side with span wire are used. With aesthetics in mind a minimum number of traction poles are used and whenever possible the wire is anchored onto neighbouring buildings. Supertram, [[Sheffield City Council]] and landlords were in talks to try and hide anchor points as much as possible and blend them into the structures.\n\nThe contact wires are twin cadmium copper ones, twin wires being necessary because of the high installed power rating of the trams (1 megawatt). The [[regenerative braking]] on the tram feeds current back into the wires.\n\n===Operation===\n[[File:Sheffield Supertram - Cab 07-04.jpg|thumb|The driving cab of a [[Siemens-Duewag Supertram]], heading towards Castle Square from Ponds Forge/Fitzalan Square.]]\nThe rules of operation of the Sheffield Supertram are similar to those of a traditional [[railway company|railway]]. Unlike normal trains, tramways can be operated without signalling, although block signalling is sometimes necessary on single-line sections. The trams are driven on a line-of-sight basis, so that the tram can be stopped if an obstruction is spotted ahead.{{Citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n\nSignals, however, are used to give indications to tram drivers when running on-street and at street crossings. As trams have priority<ref>{{cite web |last= Collier |first=Brent |url=http://www.jctconsultancy.co.uk/Symposium/Symposium2017/PapersForDownload/Sprucing%20Up%20Your%20ITS%20Brent%20Collier%20and%20Stephanie%20Cooper%20Sheffield%20City%20Council.pdf |title=JCT Symposium 2017: Sprucing up your ITS|accessdate=30 November 2018}}</ref> at many places, it was necessary to give them different traffic light phases from motor traffic and therefore different types of indication have to be used from those applicable to motor vehicles. Signal phases for the tramway are specifically modified to account for the length of the tram. The tram signals are usually operated alongside and in conjunction with traffic signals. Signals consist of white lights arranged vertically (for go), horizontally (for stop) and a cross (for caution). Two other light arrangement indicate a point direction at junctions.\n\n{{clear}}\n'''Tramway signals'''\n<gallery perrow=\"4\">\nFile:Tramway signalling - Proceed.svg|Proceed.\nFile:Tramway signalling - Stop.svg|Stop.\nFile:Tramway signalling - Caution.svg|Caution and proceed.\nFile:Tramway signalling - Turning left.svg|Turning left and proceed.\nFile:Tramway signalling - Turning right.svg|Turning right and proceed.\n</gallery>\n'''Junction signals'''\n<gallery>\nFile:Tramway signalling - Junction signalling - turning left.png|Points set for left.\nFile:Tramway signalling - Junction signalling - turning right.png|Points set for right.\nFile:Tramway signalling - Junction signalling - stop.png|Points misaligned or not detected.\n</gallery>\n\nPoints indicators are provided at junctions to indicate the route which is set through the points. At junctions, where Supertram and train movements can conflict with road traffic, fixed signals are provided in addition to points indicators. A points indicator may only be passed if it displays the correct route indication for the tram concerned and, where fixed signals are provided, if both points indicators and fixed signals are set for the correct route.\n\nLine-side signals give instructions or warnings to tram drivers. To distinguish them from normal road signs, they are diamond-shaped. The most common are speed restrictions which are in miles per hour. These are particularly necessary on road-running where trams travel along with road traffic.\n\nThe route a tram is to take is computer-controlled. The route is set on a device in the tram before a journey is started, and on approach to junctions, a signal is sent from the tram to a device known as a VIS loop buried beneath the track. This automatically sets the points in the correct direction.\n\n===Depot===\n[[File:Supertram Sheffield Station 05-07-04.jpg|thumb|[[Siemens-Duewag Supertram]] 122, operating the Purple Route to Herdings Park, on the [[permanent way]] leaving [[Sheffield station]] for [[Sheffield College]] (Granville Road) in July 2004]]\nThe depot is located at Nunnery Square and occupies the former carriage sidings alongside the [[Sheffield to Lincoln Line|Sheffield-Lincoln railway line]]. It was designed and constructed by [[Balfour Beatty]] on {{Convert|2.6|ha}} of land and consists of a three-line workshop building, six stabling sidings, a turning loop, engineers sidings and sundry equipment.{{Citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n\nThe main offices and reception, supervisor's offices, plant room, staff mess rooms, paint shop, first aid are on the first floor level on the South side of the building. The south-west of the building is home to the Operations and Power Controller's office, where live control of the running of the service is monitored using SCADA, [[Closed-circuit television|CCTV]] and radio contact. The depot substation is also located in the south-west corner, two 600&nbsp;kVA transformer-rectifiers supply the tramway overhead and an 800&nbsp;kVA transformer feeds the depot facilities.{{Citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n\nIn the workshop itself are two through-running lines (numbered 8 and 9) and line 10, a stub end. All lines have inspection pits and line 8 possesses a Hegenscheidt [[Metal lathe#Wheel lathe|wheel lathe]]. This machine allows wheel turning whilst both sets of doors are closed. The [[Wheelset (railroad)|wheelsets]] are turned in situ. High level access is provided on lines 9 and 10 for servicing of equipment boxes and pantographs. An automated washing machine is located on line 7. The site's security is provided by [[Closed-circuit television|CCTV]] and fence guarding and is under control of security personnel housed in the operations centre. Road access is from Woodbourn Road at the end of the depot.{{Citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n\nThe site was, before the arrival of Supertram, already dedicated to the railway industry, [[Nunnery engine shed]] filled most of the site whilst lines of the [[Midland Railway]], [[Great Central Railway]] and [[London & North Eastern Railway]] irrigated the area and served [[colliery|collieries]].\n\n===Tram stop design===\n[[File:Donetsk Way Tram Stop. - geograph.org.uk - 305291.jpg|thumb|Donetsk Way tram stop. The platform edge's alignment and rugged paving can be seen.]]\nThe Supertram has 50 stops,<ref>{{cite web |last= Courtenay |first=Peter |url=http://www.thetrams.co.uk/factsnfigures.php?section=supertram |title=Sheffield Supertram: Facts and figures |accessdate=19 August 2007 |format= |work= }}</ref> which are generally {{Convert|26.5|m|abbr = on}} long and {{Convert|3|m|abbr = on}} deep and are of a network-wide standard making them easy to understand and use. The design incorporates recommendations made by the [[Cranfield Institute of Technology]] who studied ergonomics for both able-bodied and disabled users.<ref name=\"access\">{{cite web |url=http://www.supertram.com/access.html |title=About us: Access |accessdate=19 August 2007 |work=Stagecoach Supertram website}}</ref>\n\nThe platforms are {{Convert|37.5|cm|abbr = on}} high, with a 1:20&nbsp;slope. The platform edge comprises a {{Convert|60|cm|abbr = on|adj = on}} wide light-coloured textured paving with strips of {{Convert|40|cm|abbr = on|adj = on}} wide edge warning tactile strip. Directional guidance tactile paving crosses the width of the platform to coincide with the tram door locations.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.stagecoachbus.com/supertram/accessibility-of-our-trams|title=Accessibility of our trams|accessdate=5 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Notable structures===\nThe Supertram network possesses a few remarkable [[structures]]. Two [[viaducts]] and one underpass are of interest: the two viaducts carry Supertram onto Park Square (a major road junction in the centre of the city), one of them being a six-span viaduct, the other the [[Tied arch bridge|bowstring]] steel arch [[Park Square Bridge]]. The underpass takes the tram underneath the busy [[A57 road|A57]] roundabout outside the [[University of Sheffield]].\n\n===Ticketing===\nPrior to the Stagecoach takeover, ticketing was done via ticket machines, provided by Abberfield Technology of Australia. These blue ticket machines dispensed adult single ride tickets, senior citizen concessionary tickets and child concessionary tickets. As well as singles, the machines sold multi-packs at a discount. Fare tables were shown on the machines with the validity of the different prices. To travel, each ticket had to be validated in a yellow machine on the platform. The ticket defined the type of passenger and trip. On validation, an overprint was added, giving the tramstop code, time and date of validation and the point of validation.{{Citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n\nAs the machines did not dispense change, nearby shop-owners were often asked for change to purchase tickets from the machines. There were also problems with machine reliability.{{Citation needed|date=May 2018}} When Stagecoach took over South Yorkshire Supertram, it removed the ticket machines and began selling tickets on board. This change brought two key positives: an improved staff presence on board each tram, and meant that passenger's tickets could be systematically checked.\n\nStagecoach Sheffield period tickets are valid on the trams and on Stagecoach buses, and period SYPTE tickets covering Sheffield or the whole of South Yorkshire are valid on Supertram as well as buses and trains. Unlike some other tramway and light rail operators in England, Supertram accepts [[English National Concessionary Travel Scheme|concessionary travel passes]] issued by any English local authority.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.supertram.com/ticketinformation.html | title=Stagecoach Supertram Ticket Information | accessdate=4 January 2010 | publisher=[[Stagecoach Group]] }}</ref> [[PlusBus]] tickets are accepted as well.\n{{clear|right}}\n\n==Opening dates==\n\n* 21 March 1994: Fitzalan Square to Meadowhall\n* 22 August 1994: Fitzalan Square to Spring Lane\n* 5 December 1994: Spring Lane to Gleadless Townend\n* 18 February 1995: Fitzalan Square to Cathedral\n* 17 February 1995: Cathedral to Shalesmoor\n* 27 March 1995: Gleadless Townend to Halfway\n* 3 April 1995: Gleadless Townend to Herdings Park\n* 23 October 1995: Shalesmoor to Middlewood/Malin Bridge\n* 25 October 2018: Tinsley/Meadowhall South to Rotherham Parkgate (tram-train)\n==Corporate affairs==\n===Ownership and structure===\nThe system is owned by the [[South Yorkshire Passenger Transport Executive]] (SYPTE), which in turn is controlled by the [[Sheffield City Region Combined Authority]], which consists of representatives from the metropolitan boroughs of [[Sheffield]], [[Metropolitan Borough of Rotherham|Rotherham]], [[Metropolitan Borough of Doncaster|Doncaster]], and [[Metropolitan Borough of Barnsley|Barnsley]].\n\nSupertram is operated through an exclusive concession agreement between SYPTE and South Yorkshire Supertram Ltd (SYSL), now a wholly owned subsidiary of [[Stagecoach Group|Stagecoach Holdings PLC]]. SYSL holds the concession to operate and maintain the network until 31 March 2024. \n\n===Business trends===\nThe key trends in recent years for Sheffield Supertram are (years ending 31 March):\n[[File:399206 Parkgate.jpg|thumb|A Supertram tram-train, pictured following introduction of the service in October 2018]]\n<center>\n{| class=\"wikitable\" \n|- style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! style=\"background: #3063A5;\" | \n! style=\"background: #3063A5;\" | <span style=\"color: white\">2014</span>\n! style=\"background: #3063A5;\" | <span style=\"color: white\">2015</span>\n! style=\"background: #3063A5;\" | <span style=\"color: white\">2016</span>\n! style=\"background: #3063A5;\" | <span style=\"color: white\">2017</span>\n! style=\"background: #3063A5;\" | <span style=\"color: white\">2018</span>\n! style=\"background: #3063A5;\" | <span style=\"color: white\">2019</span>\n|-\n| Passenger revenue ([[Pound sterling|\u00a3]]m)\n| align=center|13.9\n| align=center|12.6\n| align=center|11.4\n| align=center|13.5\n| align=center|13.9\n! align=center|14.0\n|-\n| Number of passengers (m)\n| align=center|12.6\n| align=center|11.5\n| align=center|11.6\n| align=center|12.6\n| align=center|12.3\n! align=center|11.9\n|-\n| Number of trams\n| align=center|25\n| align=center|25\n| align=center|26\n| align=center|32\n| align=center|32\n! align=center|32\n|-\n| Operating performance - services on time (%)\n| align=center|\n| align=center|\n| align=center|\n| align=center|\n| align=center|\n! align=center|98.7\n|-\n| <small>''Notes/sources''</small>\n| align=\"center\" |<ref name=\"LRT\"/>\n| align=\"center\" |<ref name=\"LRT\"/>\n| align=\"center\" |<ref name=\"LRT\"/>\n| align=\"center\" |<ref name=\"LRT\"/>\n| align=\"center\" |<ref name=\"LRT\"/>\n| align=\"center\" |<ref name=\"LRT\">{{cite web |title=Light rail and tram statistics (LRT)|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/statistical-data-sets/light-rail-and-tram-statistics-lrt |publisher=Department for Transport | date=11 June 2019 |accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"2019 Report\">{{cite web |title=LSheffield Supertram Annual Report 2018/19|url=https://www.stagecoachbus.com/media-library/files/supertram/flyers/supertram%20annual%20report%202018-19.pdf?la=en |publisher=Stagecoach | date=June 2019 |accessdate=8 April 2020}}</ref>\n|}\n</center>\n\n===Passenger numbers===\nDetailed passenger journeys since Supertram commenced operations in May 1994 were:\n{|class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! colspan=\"11\" style=\"background:#3063A5; color:white;\"|'''Estimated passenger journeys made on Sheffield Supertram per financial year (to 31 March)'''\n|-\n! style=\"background:#3063A5; color:white;\"|Year\n! style=\"background:#3063A5; color:white;\"|Passenger<br>journeys\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:#fff;\"|<!---blank--->\n! style=\"background:#3063A5; color:white;\"|Year\n! style=\"background:#3063A5; color:white;\"|Passenger<br>journeys\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:#fff;\"|<!---blank--->\n! style=\"background:#3063A5; color:white;\"|Year\n! style=\"background:#3063A5; color:white;\"|Passenger<br>journeys\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:#fff;\"|<!---blank--->\n! style=\"background:#3063A5; color:white;\"|Year\n! style=\"background:#3063A5; color:white;\"|Passenger<br>journeys\n|-\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 1994/95\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 2.2m\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:#fff;\" rowspan=\"8\"|\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 2002/03\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 11.5m\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:#fff;\" rowspan=\"8\"|\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 2010/11\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 15.0m\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:#fff;\" rowspan