r:black;\"| 11.6m\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| \n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| \n|-\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 2000/01\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 11.9m\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 2008/09\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 15.0m\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 2016/17\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 12.6m\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| \n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| \n|-\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 2001/02\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 11.4m\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 2009/10\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 14.7m\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 2017/18\n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| 12.3m\n! style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| \n| style=\"background:#fff; color:black;\"| \n|-\n| colspan=\"11\" style=\"background:#fff; font-size:90%;\"|Estimates from the [[Department for Transport]]<ref name=\"dftjour\">{{cite web |title=Passenger journeys on light rail and trams by system: England - annual from 1983/84 |url=https://assets.publishing.service.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/719478/lrt0101.ods |publisher=Department For Transport |accessdate=14 June 2019 |format=downloadable .ods [[OpenDocument]] file}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Future, past plans, delays and cost overruns==\nThe proposed extensions to the Supertram network have undergone many changes over time, with some being cancelled and others running over budget and suffering from delays in their implementation.\n\nIn May 2003 the [[South Yorkshire Passenger Transport Executive|South Yorkshire Passenger Transport Authority]] announced plans to extend the Supertram network to [[Hellaby]], a suburb of [[Rotherham]], [[Dore]], a suburb of Sheffield and [[Ranmoor]], Sheffield. So far, in February 2020 none of these extensions, estimated (in 2003) to cost a total of \u00a3400&nbsp;million has been built.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/south_yorkshire/3011725.stm|title=Supertram extension plans revealed|last=|first=|date=8 May 2003|work=|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/mobile/england/bradford/7303727.stm|title=Tram-trains to get first UK trial|last=|first=|date=18 March 2008|work=|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn August 2008 plans were announced for the trial of [[Hybrid vehicle|diesel-electro hybrid tram trains]] on a route via [[Network Rail]] tracks to [[Huddersfield railway station|Huddersfield]] via [[Meadowhall Interchange|Meadowhall]], [[Barnsley Interchange|Barnsley]] and [[Penistone railway station|Penistone]]. The fleet of five tram trains, costing \u00a39&nbsp;million was expected to be in operation by the end of 2010 with the whole project costing \u00a324&nbsp;million for the 37 mile route. It was planned that the hourly [[Northern Rail (Serco-Abellio)|Northern Rail]] service from Barnsley to Huddersfield would be scrapped, being replaced by a more frequent tram service with more stops and a faster service due to the trams' more rapid acceleration. Plans were also announced for a second trial between [[Rotherham Central railway station|Rotherham Central]] and Sheffield at the same time.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.railnews.co.uk/news/2008/08/05-northern-rail-tram-train.html|title=Penistone line is chosen for \u00a324m tram trains trial|last=|first=|date=5 August 2008|website=Rail News|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn September 2009 plans for the Sheffield to Huddersfield route were abandoned.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.railwaygazette.com/news/single-view/view/rotherham-tram-train-replaces-penistone-scheme.html|title=Rotherham tram-train replaces Penistone scheme|last=UK|first=DVV Media|date=|work=Railway Gazette International|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref> The Sheffield to Rotherham route was to go ahead, with trams using a Network Rail freight line. The initial plan was to use electric vehicles capable of operating on either 750\u00a0V DC or 25\u00a0kV AC. Trams are planned to go via Rotherham Central to a new station at Rotherham Parkgate. The scheme was estimated to require \u00a315&nbsp;million, later revised upwards to \u00a318.7&nbsp;million to build when first proposed, but was eventually expected to cost \u00a375.1m. The proposed route was to have been in operation by 2015, later put back until October 2018 after a series of delays.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-south-yorkshire-34473670|title=Tram-train scheme delayed by year|last=|first=|date=8 October 2015|work=BBC News|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-south-yorkshire-36315711|title=Further delays for tram-train pilot|date=18 May 2016|work=BBC News|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-south-yorkshire-40482427|title=Tram-train scheme costs spiral to \u00a375m|date=4 July 2017|work=BBC News|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref> Part of the delay was due the transport secretary to failing to approve the building of a 150m (164yd) section of track at [[Tinsley, South Yorkshire|Tinsley]] in a timely manner.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/mobile/england/south_yorkshire/8257652.stm|title=City tram-trains trial unveiled|date=15 September 2009|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref> The [[Public Accounts Committee (United Kingdom)|Public Accounts Committee]] (PAC) was critical of Network Rail's initial estimates for the cost of modifications to the route calling them, \"wholly unrealistic\". The PAC also noted that Network Rail and the [[Department for Transport]] could not provide figures on how much money had been spent on a now cancelled [[Railway electrification system|line electrification]] project.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-south-yorkshire-42354784|title=Tram-train pilot failings anger MPs|last=|first=|date=15 December 2017|work=BBC News|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rothbiz.co.uk/2017/12/news-5830-sheffield-rotherham-tram.html|title=News: Sheffield-Rotherham tram-train pilot - \"how not to run a rail project\"|last=|first=|date=|website=Rothbiz.co.uk|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref> Part of the unexpected rise in the cost of creating the route and the delay was due to the need to demolish and rebuild the College Road road over-bridge next to Rotherham Central station. It was thought that the [[Track ballast|ballast]] beneath the railway line could have been excavated to provide headroom for the [[Overhead line|catenary]] but this proved not to be feasible.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rotherhamadvertiser.co.uk/news/view,tram-works-mean-fourmonth-closure-for-town-centre-road_22268.htm|title=Tram works mean four-month closure for town centre road|last=Upton|first=Michael|date=13 April 2017|work=Rotherham Advertiser|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rothbiz.co.uk/2014/06/news-4190-preparations-for-tram-train.html|title=News: Preparations for tram train|last=|first=|date=|website=Rothbiz.co.uk|accessdate=16 December 2017}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017 the [[Sheffield City Region]] invited public consultation on ''The Sheffield City Region Transport Strategy 2018-2040'' policy document (draft for consultation November 2017) in which it was revealed that only 1% of the population used the Supertram network on journeys to work in 2011.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sheffieldcityregion.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/SCR-Transport-Strategy-Consultation-Draft.pdf|title=The Sheffield City Region Transport Strategy 2018-2040 (draft - for consultation November 2017)|last=|first=|date=November 2017|website=|page=22|accessdate=9 January 2017}}</ref>\nThe number of passengers on the Supertram network increased from 2&nbsp;million in the 1994/1995 financial years to over 12&nbsp;million in the 2016/2017 financial years.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sheffieldcityregion.org.uk/wp-content/uploads/2018/01/SCR-Transport-Strategy-Consultation-Draft.pdf|title=The Sheffield City Region Transport Strategy 2018-2040 (draft - for consultation November 2017)|last=|first=|date=November 2017|website=|page=25|accessdate=9 January 2017}}</ref>\n\nThe [[tram-train]] extension to [[Rotherham]] opened on 25 October 2018, with a fleet of seven [[Vossloh]] Citylink [[British Rail Class 399|Class 399]] tram-trains. This involves trams operating on [[Network Rail]]'s line from Tinsley to [[Rotherham Central railway station|Rotherham station]] with a short extension to Rotherham Parkgate Shopping Centre, after travelling on the Supertram line from Sheffield Cathedral to Meadowhall South/Tinsley.<ref>[http://www.railwaygazette.com/nc/news/single-view/view/rotherham-tram-tram-project-funding-confirmed.html Rotherham tram-tram project funding confirmed] ''Railway Gazette International'' 17 May 2012</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thestar.co.uk/news/business/business-news/new-2017-hope-for-delayed-60m-sheffield-to-rotherham-tram-train-scheme-1-7005138|title=New 2017 hope for delayed \u00a360m Sheffield to Rotherham tram-train scheme|publisher=The Star|accessdate=27 March 2015}}</ref> The station at Rotherham Central is a combined tram stop and [[railway station]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rotherhamadvertiser.co.uk/news/100942/pioneering-tram-train-on-track-for-rotherham-launch.aspx|title=Pioneering tram train on track for Rotherham launch|last=|first=|date=|work=Rotherham Advertiser|accessdate=9 January 2018}}</ref> To cater for the tram train services, platforms 1 and 2 at Rotherham Central were extended, with the extensions being numbered platforms 3 and 4 respectively. The stop at Parkgate is a single platform terminus.\n\n==Accidents and incidents==\n\n* In 1995, engineer William Roe suffered severe [[brain damage]] after his car skidded on wet tram tracks and crashed into a metal pole. Supertram were made to award Mr Roe compensation for failing to ensure that the rails were level with the adjacent road surface, and for the lack of warning signs indicating that the tracks are hazardous when wet. It was reported there were 53 accidents involving Supertram in Sheffield between 1994 and 1997, including two fatalities and 12 serious injuries.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/uknews/1360466/Tram-firms-face-big-claims-after-crash-case.html|title=Tram firms face big claims after crash case|first=Paul |last=Stokes|date=25 October 2001|work=The Telegraph|accessdate=27 November 2014}}</ref> \n* On 7 March 2003, a man died from serious head injuries after he was hit by a tram whilst lying on the tracks.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/2832199.stm|title=Man dies in Supertram accident |work=BBC News |date=8 March 2003 |accessdate=27 November 2014}}</ref>\n* On 27 October 2005, a pedestrian was killed after stepping in front of an approaching tram.<ref>[http://www.raib.gov.uk/cms_resources.cfm?file=/060301_R012006_StaniforthRoad.pdf \"Tram, Pedestrian Collision at Staniforth Road, Sheffield, 27 October 2005.\"] ''Rail Accident Investigation Branch'', March 2006.</ref>\n* On 20 September 2008, a 75-year-old woman was seriously injured when she was fell and was subsequently struck by a tram while it was arriving at the local tram stop.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/1/hi/england/south_yorkshire/7626738.stm|website=BBC News|title=Woman badly hurt in tram accident|date=20 September 2008}}</ref> The woman was removed and transferred to the [[Northern General Hospital]], suffering from head injuries and a fractured pelvis leg.\n* On 22 October 2015, trams 120 and 118 collided at Shalesmoor. This resulted in the two damaged sections of both trams requiring major repairs, whilst the undamaged parts of trams 120 and 118 were put together and painted in a version of the original Sheffield Tramways cream and blue livery to re-create the original 120. Tram 118 returned to service a year later in October 2016.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.britishtramsonline.co.uk/news/?p=15771 |title=In Pictures: Stagecoach Supertram 118\u2019s revised look |date=15 November 2016 |work=British Trams Online |accessdate=6 June 2017}}</ref>\n* In November 2016, teacher Terry Orwin sustained serious head injuries from crashing while riding a bicycle on Langsett Road and being caught by the tram tracks.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.thestar.co.uk/news/helmet-saves-sheffield-dad-after-horror-bike-crash-1-8241727 |title=Helmet saves Sheffield dad after horror bike crash |date=16 November 2016 |work=Sheffield Star |accessdate=9 February 2017}}</ref>\n* In December 2016, Saleh Qassim Saleh, 81, was killed in collision with a tram. The driver was charged with causing death by careless driving.<ref>[https://www.thestar.co.uk/news/woman-appears-at-court-charged-over-sheffield-tram-crash-that-killed-pensioner-1-9499447 \"Woman appears at court charged over Sheffield tram crash that killed pensioner\"], ''Sheffield Star'', 18 December 2018.</ref>\n* In June 2017, two trams were involved in a low-speed collision at Halfway.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thestar.co.uk/news/breaking-sheffield-tram-crash-causing-havoc-on-public-transport-network-1-8585134|title=BREAKING: Sheffield tram crash causing havoc on public transport network|accessdate=2 August 2018}}</ref>\n* In July 2018 a passenger was injured when they were thrown across the tram as a result tram overspeeding at Middlewood Road and then braking suddenly. The impact of the passenger with a door caused the door to open.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gov.uk/government/news/passenger-injury-following-tram-overspeeding-at-middlewood-road|title=Passenger injury following tram overspeeding at Middlewood Road|work=GOV.UK|accessdate=2 August 2018}}</ref>\n* On 25 October 2018, the day the Tram-Train service launched, a lorry collided with one such tram at approximately 3.30&nbsp;pm on Staniforth Road, near the Woodbourn Road station, derailing the tram-train. Three people were injured with two being treated on site and one taken to hospital.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-south-yorkshire-45976460|title=Tram-train crashes on first day of service|date=25 October 2018|work=BBC News|accessdate=25 October 2018}}</ref> Initial reports indicate that the lorry pulled across the path of the Tram.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.itv.com/news/calendar/2018-10-25/lorry-hits-sheffield-tram/|title=Lorry collides with Sheffield tram-train on first day of new service|publisher=|work=ITV News|accessdate=25 October 2018}}</ref> On 12 August 2019, lorry driver Kevin Hague, 61, of Rotherham admitted driving through a red light at Sheffield Magistrates' Court. The BBC reported, 'In a personal impact statement read to the court the driver of the tram-train said he was thankful he was in one of the new \u00a34m vehicles. They are built to higher crash-worthiness standards as they also run on Network Rail tracks.'<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-south-yorkshire-49319941|title=Lorry driver fined over tram-train crash|last=|first=|date=12 August 2019|work=BBC News|access-date=12 August 2019|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n* On 30 November 2018, a car collided with a tram-train at approximately 4.30 pm on Staniforth Road.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-south-yorkshire-46407052|title=Three injured as tram and car collide in Sheffield|publisher=|work=BBC News|accessdate=30 November 2018}}</ref>\n* On 22 May 2019, a man was hit by a tram shortly after having an argument with two men.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-south-yorkshire-48381290|title=Man seriously injured by Sheffield tram after argument|publisher=|work=BBC News|accessdate=26 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Man suffers serious injuries after being hit by tram in Sheffield |url=http://www.britishtramsonline.co.uk/news/?p=27783 |website=British Trams Online |accessdate=26 May 2019}}</ref> He later died on 26 May 2019 and was named as Martin Rigg.<ref>{{cite web |title=Man hit by tram in Sheffield dies in hospital |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-south-yorkshire-48413602 |website=BBC News |accessdate=26 May 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Sheffield tram death man named as Martin Rigg |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-south-yorkshire-48432084 |website=BBC News |accessdate=6 June 2019}}</ref> A man was arrested on suspicion of murder on 1 June 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Murder arrest over Martin Rigg Sheffield tram death |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-south-yorkshire-48483685 |website=BBC News |accessdate=6 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Sheffield Tramway]] \u2013 the original Sheffield tramway system.\n* [[Light Rail Transit Association]]\n* [[List of town tramway systems in England]]\n* [[List of town tramway systems in the United Kingdom]]\n\n==References==\n;Notes\n{{notelist-lr}}\n;Citations\n\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Sheffield Supertram}}\n{{Attached KML|display=title,inline}}\n* [http://www.supertram.com/ Supertram website]\n* [http://www.thetrams.co.uk/supertram/ Stagecoach Supertram at thetrams.co.uk]\n* [http://bbs.keyhole.com/ubb/showthreaded.php/Cat/0/Number/240058 Collection of Google Earth locations of Stagecoach Supertram stops] (Requires [http://earth.google.com Google Earth software]) from the Google Earth Community forum.\n* [http://www.supertram.com/uploads/vehicleinfo.pdf Supertram specs]\n\n{{Stagecoach Sheffield Supertram}}\n{{UK light rail}}\n{{Britishmetros}}\n{{StagecoachGroup}}\n\n[[Category:Stagecoach Group rail services]]\n[[Category:Sheffield Supertram| ]]\n[[Category:Railway lines opened in 1994]]\n[[Category:1994 establishments in England]]\n[[Category:Light rail in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Tram transport in England]]\n[[Category:750 V DC railway electrification]]\n", "name_user": "Bob1960evens", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFuture, past plans, delays and cost overruns:grammar", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sheffield_Supertram"}
{"title_page": "Kingdom of the Two Sicilies", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{short description|Italian state (pre-unification)}}\n{{Infobox country\n| native_name                = {{native name|it|Regno delle Due Sicilie}}<br/>{{native name|nap|Regno d\u2019\u2019e Ddoje Sicilie}}<br/>{{native name|scn|Regnu d\u00ee Dui Sicili}}\n| conventional_long_name                = Kingdom of the Two Sicilies\n| common_name                = Two Sicilies||\n| life_span                = 1816\u20131861\n| event_pre                = Edict of [[Bayonne]]<ref>{{cite book|author=Pietro Colletta|title=History of the kingdom of Naples: 1734\u20131825|url=https://archive.org/details/historykingdomn04collgoog|year=1858|publisher=T. Constable and Co.|page=[https://archive.org/details/historykingdomn04collgoog/page/n184 71]}}</ref><ref>[http://bp3.blogger.com/_24klMrIuq58/Rl6iFe3-oZI/AAAAAAAAANE/Ys2vdy9W3rA/s1600-h/Murat1.jpg. Proclaims with Murat's title]. {{in lang|it}}</ref>\n| event_start                = Edict of [[Ferdinand I of the Two Sicilies|Ferdinand IV of Naples]]\n| year_start                = 12 December 1816\n| event1                = [[Expedition of the Thousand|Garibaldi's landing in Sicily]]\n| date_event1                = 5 May 1860\n| event_end                = [[Italian unification|Declaration of Unification]]\n| year_end                = 17 March 1861|\n| p1                = Kingdom of Sicily\n| flag_p1                = Bandiera del Regno di Sicilia 4.svg\n| p2                = Kingdom of Naples\n| flag_p2                = Bandera de N%C3%A1poles - Trast%C3%A1mara.svg\n| s1                = Kingdom of Italy\n| flag_s1                = Flag of Italy (1861-1946) crowned.svg|\n| image_flag                = Flag of the Kingdom of the Two Sicilies (1738).svg\n| flag_type                = [[Kingdom of the Two Sicilies#Flags of the Kingdom of the Two Sicilies|Flag<br>(1816\u20131848; 1849\u20131860)]]\n| image_coat                = Great Royal Coat of Arms of theTwo Sicilies.svg\n| image_map                = Kingdom_of_the_Two_Sicilies_within_Europe_in_1839.svg\n| image_map_caption                = Location of the '''Kingdom of the Two Sicilies''' within Europe in 1839|\n| capital                = [[Palermo]] {{Small|(1816\u20131817)}}<br>[[Naples]] {{Small|(1817\u20131861)}}\n| national_motto                = \n| national_anthem                = \"[[Inno al Re]]\"<br><small>(\"Hymn to the King\")</small><center>[[File:Giovanni Paisiello - Inno al Re \u2014 Inno nazionale del Regno delle Due Sicilie.ogg]]</center>\n| common_languages                = [[Neapolitan language|Neapolitan]]<br/>[[Sicilian language|Sicilian]]<br/>[[Italian language|Italian]]<br/>[[Molise Croatian]]<br/>[[Gallo-Italic of Sicily]]<br/>[[Gallo-Italic of Basilicata]]<br/>[[Franco-Proven\u00e7al language|Franco-Proven\u00e7al]]<br/>[[Occitan language|Occitan]]<br/>[[Griko language|Griko]]<br/>[[Calabrian Greek|Greek-Bovesian]]<br/>[[Arberesh language|Arberesh]]\n| religion                = [[Roman Catholicism]]\n| currency                = [[Two Sicilies ducat]]\n| government_type                = [[Absolute monarchy]]<br>{{Small|(1816\u20131848; 1849\u20131861)}}<br>[[Constitutional monarchy]]<br>{{Small|(1848\u20131849)}}\n| title_leader                = [[List of monarchs of the Two Sicilies|King]]\n| leader1                = [[Ferdinand I of the Two Sicilies|Ferdinand I]] {{Small|(first)}}\n| year_leader1                = 1816\u20131825\n| leader2                = [[Francis II of the Two Sicilies|Francis II]] {{Small|(last)}}\n| year_leader2                = 1859\u20131861\n| today                = [[Italy]]<br />[[Croatia]]{{anchor|infoa}}<sup>[[#inforefa|[a]]]</sup>\n| footnotes                = {{anchor|inforefa}}a. '''[[#infoa|^]]''' The archipelago of [[Palagru\u017ea]] was part of the province of Capitanata.\n| demonym                = \n| area_km2                = \n| area_rank                = \n| GDP_PPP                = \n| GDP_PPP_year                = \n| HDI                = \n| HDI_year                = \n| population_estimate                = 9,281,279 (1859/60)\n}}\n\n{{More citations needed|date=April 2018}}{{About|the kingdom from 1816 to 1860|the kingdom from 1130 to 1282|Kingdom of Sicily}}\n\nThe '''Kingdom of the Two Sicilies''' ({{lang-nap|Regno d\u2019\u2019e Ddoje Sicilie}}; {{lang-scn|Regnu d\u00ee Dui Sicili}}; {{lang-it|Regno delle Due Sicilie}}; {{lang-es|Reino de las Dos Sicilias}})<ref>{{Cite book|last=Swinburne|first=Henry |authorlink = Henry Swinburne|title=Travels in the Two Sicilies (1790)|publisher=British Library|url=https://archive.org/details/travelsintwosic00swingoog|quote=two sicilies.|year=1790 }}</ref> was a kingdom located in [[Southern Italy]] from 1816\u20131860.<ref>{{Cite book|last=De Sangro |first= Michele |title= I Borboni nel Regno delle Due Sicilie |year= 2003 |publisher= Edizioni Caponi |location= Lecce |language=it}}</ref> The kingdom was the largest sovereign state by population and size in [[Italy]] prior to [[Italian unification]], comprising Sicily and all of [[Italian Peninsula|Peninsula Italy]] south of the [[Papal States]], covering most of the area of today's [[Mezzogiorno]].\n\nThe kingdom was formed when the [[Kingdom of Sicily]] merged with the [[Kingdom of Naples]], which was officially known as the Kingdom of Sicily. Since both kingdoms were named Sicily, they were collectively known as the \"Two Sicilies\" (''Utraque Sicilia'', literally \"both Sicilies\"), and the unified kingdom adopted this name. The King of the Two Sicilies was [[Expedition of the Thousand|overthrown by Giuseppe Garibaldi]] in 1860, after which the people voted in a [[plebiscite]] to join the [[House of Savoy|Savoyard]] [[Kingdom of Sardinia]]. The annexation of the Two Sicilies completed the first phase of [[Italian unification]], and the new [[Kingdom of Italy (1861\u20131946)|Kingdom of Italy]] was proclaimed in 1861.\n\nThe Two Sicilies were heavily agricultural, like the other Italian states.<ref>{{cite web|author=Nicola Zitara|url=http://www.eleaml.org/e_book/unitruff_cap1.pdf|title=La legge di Archimede: L'accumulazione selvaggia nell'Italia unificata e la nascita del colonialismo interno|publisher=Eleaml-Fora!|language=Italian}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Name==\nThe name \"Two Sicilies\" originated from the partition of the medieval [[Kingdom of Sicily]]. Until 1285, the island of [[Sicily]] and the [[Mezzogiorno]] were constituent parts of the Kingdom of Sicily. As a result of the [[War of the Sicilian Vespers]] (1282\u20131302),<ref name=\"dieli\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.dieli.net/SicilyPage/History/SicilianHist.html|publisher=Dieli.net|title=Sicilian History|date=7 October 2007}}</ref> the King of Sicily lost the Island of Sicily (also called Trinacria) to the [[Crown of Aragon]], but remained ruler over the peninsular part of the realm. Although his territory became known unofficially as the [[Kingdom of Naples]], he and his successors never gave up the title \"King of Sicily\" and still officially referred to their realm as the \"Kingdom of Sicily\". At the same time, the Aragonese rulers of the Island of Sicily also called their realm the \"Kingdom of Sicily\". Thus, there were two kingdoms called \"Sicily\":<ref name=\"dieli\" /> hence, the '''Two Sicilies'''.\n\n==Background==\n\n===Origins of the two kingdoms===\n{{Main|Kingdom of Sicily|Kingdom of Naples}}\n[[File:Chapelle Palatine.jpg|thumb|150px|[[Cappella Palatina]], church of first unifier [[Roger II of Sicily]].]]\nIn 1130 the [[Normans|Norman]] king [[Roger II of Sicily|Roger II]] formed the [[Kingdom of Sicily]] by combining the [[County of Sicily]] with the southern part of the Italian Peninsula (then known as the [[Duchy of Apulia and Calabria]]) as well as with the [[Maltese Islands]]. The capital of this kingdom was [[Palermo]]&nbsp;\u2014 which is on the island of [[Sicily]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Oldfield|first=Paul|date=2017|title=Alexander of Telese's Encomium of Capua and the Formation of the Kingdom of Sicily|url=https://www.research.manchester.ac.uk/portal/files/47249890/Oldfield_History_revised_.pdf|url-status=live|journal=[[History (journal)|History]]|volume=|pages=183\u2013200|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190427101137/https://www.research.manchester.ac.uk/portal/files/47249890/Oldfield_History_revised_.pdf|archive-date=April 27, 2019|via=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Oldfield|first=Paul|chapter=Italo-Norman Empire|date=2015|encyclopedia=The Encyclopedia of Empire|volume=|pages=1\u20133|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|language=en|doi=10.1002/9781118455074.wbeoe004|isbn=978-1-118-45507-4|title=The Encyclopedia of Empire: A-C}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/place/Kingdom-of-the-Two-Sicilies|title=Kingdom of the Two Sicilies {{!}} historical kingdom, Italy|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref>\n\nDuring the reign of [[Charles I of Naples|Charles I]] of [[Capetian House of Anjou|Anjou]] (1266\u20131285),<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ij0rDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA3|title=The Clement Bible at the Medieval Courts of Naples and Avignon: \"A Story of Papal Power, Royal Prestige, and Patronage \"|last=Fleck|first=CathleenA|date=2017-07-05|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-351-54553-2|location=|pages=3|language=en}}</ref> the [[War of the Sicilian Vespers]] (1282\u20131302) split the kingdom.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Shneidman|first=J. Lee|date=1960|title=Aragon and the War of the Sicilian Vespers|journal=The Historian|volume=22|issue=3|pages=250\u2013263|issn=0018-2370|jstor=24437629|doi=10.1111/j.1540-6563.1960.tb01657.x}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qTDfAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA449|title=Dictionary of Wars|last=Kohn|first=George Childs|date=2013-10-31|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-135-95494-9|location=|pages=449|language=en}}</ref> Charles, who was of French origin, lost the island of Sicily to the [[House of Barcelona]], who were from [[Crown of Aragon|Aragon]] and [[Catalan people|Catalan]].<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=E2CTAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT1063|title=Medieval Italy: An Encyclopedia|last=Kleinhenz|first=Christopher|date=2004-08-02|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-135-94880-1|location=|pages=1103|language=en}}</ref>  Charles remained king of the peninsular region, which became informally known as the [[Kingdom of Naples]]. Officially Charles never gave up the title of \"The Kingdom of Sicily\", thus there existed two separate kingdoms calling themselves \"Sicily\".<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=0fwxAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA63|title=Southern Italy in the Late Middle Ages: Demographic, Institutional and Economic Change in the Kingdom of Naples, c.1440-c.1530|last=Sakellariou|first=Eleni|date=2011-12-09|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-22405-6|location=|pages=63|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Aragonese and Spanish direct rule===\n{{Main|Crown of Aragon|Spanish Empire}}\n[[File:Imperi de la Corona d'Arag\u00f3.png|thumb|left|180px|Crown of Aragon, greatest extent]]\nOnly with the [[Peace of Caltabellotta]] (1302), sponsored by [[Pope Boniface VIII]], did the two kings of \"Sicily\" recognize each other's legitimacy; the island kingdom then became the \"[[Kingdom of Trinacria]]\" in official contexts,<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TNs3BQAAQBAJ&pg=PT847|title=Medieval Italy: An Encyclopedia|last=Kleinhenz|first=Christopher|date=2004-08-02|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-135-94879-5|location=|pages=847|language=en}}</ref> though the populace still called it Sicily.<ref name=\"dieli\"/>{{Better source|date=December 2019}} In 1442, [[Alfonso V of Aragon]], king of insular Sicily, conquered Naples and became king of both.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xVMJAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT716|title=A History of Medieval Spain|last=O'Callaghan|first=Joseph F.|date=2013-11-12|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=978-0-8014-6871-1|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CcfzAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA19|title=The Italians|last=Hooper|first=John|date=2015-01-29|publisher=Penguin|isbn=978-0-698-18364-3|location=|pages=19|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAlfonso V called his kingdom in [[Latin]] \"''Regnum Utriusque Sicili\u00e6\"'', meaning \"Kingdom of both Sicilies\".<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nZm3Mj9yRJYC&pg=PT210|title=Vanished Kingdoms: The Rise and Fall of States and Nations|last=Davies|first=Norman|date=2012-01-05|publisher=Penguin|isbn=978-1-101-54534-8|location=|pages=210|language=en}}</ref> At the death of Alfonso in 1458, the kingdom again became divided between his brother [[John II of Aragon]], who kept the island of Sicily, and his illegitimate son [[Ferdinand I of Naples|Ferdinand]], who became King of Naples.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/encyclopaediabri13kell|title=The Encyclopaedia Britannica: latest edition. A dictionary of arts, sciences and general literature|last=Kellogg|first=Day Otis|last2=Smith|first2=William Robertson|date=1902|publisher=Werner|isbn=|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/encyclopaediabri13kell/page/478 478]|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /> In 1501, King [[Ferdinand II of Aragon]], the son of John II, agreed to help [[Louis XII of France]] conquer Naples and [[Milan]]. After [[Frederick of Naples|Frederick IV]] was forced to abdicate, the French took power, and Louis reigned as Louis III of Naples for three years. Negotiations to divide the region failed, and the French soon began unsuccessful attempts to force the Spanish out of the peninsula.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1LCJDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA151|title=The Spanish Empire: A Historical Encyclopedia [2 volumes]: A Historical Encyclopedia|last=Tarver|first=H. Micheal|last2=Slape|first2=Emily|date=2016-07-25|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-61069-422-3|location=|pages=151|language=en}}</ref> \n\nAfter the French lost the [[Battle of Garigliano (1503)|Battle of Garigliano]] (1503), they left the kingdom. Ferdinand II then re-united the two areas into one kingdom.<ref name=\":4\" /> From 1516, when [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor]] became the first [[King of Spain]], both Naples and Sicily came under direct Spanish rule.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/place/Italy|title=Italy - The age of Charles V|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref> In 1530 Charles V granted the islands of [[Malta]] and [[Gozo]], which had been part of the Kingdom of Sicily, to the [[Knights Hospitaller]] (thereafter known as the [[Order of Malta]]).<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/descriptionmalt03badggoog|title=Description of Malta and Gozo|last=Badger|first=George Percy|date=1838|publisher=M. Weiss|isbn=|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/descriptionmalt03badggoog/page/n39 19]\u201320|language=en}}</ref> At the end of the [[War of the Spanish Succession]], the [[Treaty of Utrecht]] in 1713 granted Sicily to the [[Duke of Savoy]],<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nodOAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA426|title=Memoirs of the affairs of Europe from the Peace of Utrecht|last=|first=|date=1824|publisher=Murray|isbn=|location=|pages=426|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lCJBDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT263|title=Britain, Spain and the Treaty of Utrecht 1713-2013|last=Dadson|first=Trevor J.|date=2017-12-02|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-351-19133-3|language=en}}</ref> until the [[Treaty of Rastatt]] in 1714 left Naples to the [[Charles VI, Holy Roman Emperor|Emperor Charles VI]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xhGFCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA207|title=Wars That Changed History: 50 of the World's Greatest Conflicts: 50 of the World's Greatest Conflicts|last=Tucker|first=Spencer C.|date=2015-09-22|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-61069-786-6|location=|pages=270|language=en}}</ref> In the 1720 [[Treaty of The Hague (1720)|Treaty of The Hague]], the Emperor and Savoy exchanged Sicily for [[Sardinia]], thus reuniting Naples and Sicily.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a_QLAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA670|title=Italy|last=Williams|first=Henry Smith|date=1907|work=The Times|isbn=|location=|pages=670|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4Joqn8mzOXwC&pg=PA121|title=Warfare on the Mediterranean in the Age of Sail: A History, 1571-1866|last=Blackmore|first=David S. T.|date=2014-01-10|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-7864-5784-7|location=|pages=121|language=en}}</ref><!--<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xVMJAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT716|title=A History of Medieval Spain|last=O'Callaghan|first=Joseph F.|date=2013-11-12|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=978-0-8014-6871-1|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CcfzAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA19|title=The Italians|last=Hooper|first=John|date=2015-01-29|publisher=Penguin|year=|isbn=978-0-698-18364-3|location=|pages=19|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"waller\">Waller, Maureen. ''Sovereign Ladies: The Six Reigning Queens of England''. St. Martin's Press (New York), 2006. {{ISBN|0-312-33801-5}}.</ref>-->\n<!--<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xVMJAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT716|title=A History of Medieval Spain|last=O'Callaghan|first=Joseph F.|date=2013-11-12|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=978-0-8014-6871-1|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CcfzAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA19|title=The Italians|last=Hooper|first=John|date=2015-01-29|publisher=Penguin|year=|isbn=978-0-698-18364-3|location=|pages=19|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"waller\">Waller, Maureen. ''Sovereign Ladies: The Six Reigning Queens of England''. St. Martin's Press (New York), 2006. {{ISBN|0-312-33801-5}}.</ref>-->\n\n==History==\n\n===Unification of the Crowns===\n[[File:Ferdinand IV of Naples.jpg|thumb|140px|[[Ferdinand I of the Two Sicilies|Ferdinand I]]]]\n\nIn 1735, during the [[War of the Polish Succession]], [[Charles III of Spain|Charles, Duke of Parma]], defeated the occupying Austrians and became Charles III of Naples and Sicily.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Black|first=Jeremy|date=1986|title=British Neutrality in the War of the Polish Succession, 1733-1735|journal=The International History Review|volume=8|issue=3|pages=345\u2013366|issn=0707-5332|jstor=40105627|doi=10.1080/07075332.1986.9640416}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Rm1e0nWo5N8C&pg=PA141|title=Italy: A Short History|last=Hearder|first=Harry|last2=Morris|first2=Jonathan|date=2001-12-13|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-00072-7|location=|pages=141, 143|language=en}}</ref> In 1759, Charles became King Carlos III of Spain and resigned Sicily and Naples to his younger son, who became [[Ferdinand III of Sicily]] and Ferdinand IV of Naples.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://research.britishmuseum.org/research/search_the_collection_database/term_details.aspx?bioId=87575|title=Term details|website=British Museum|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref>\n\nIn January 1799, [[Jean-\u00c9tienne Championnet]], a general of the [[French First Republic]], captured Naples and proclaimed the [[Parthenopaean Republic]], a French client state, as successor to the kingdom.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1QyXCTW_MCQC&pg=PT670|title=The Wiley-Blackwell Dictionary of Modern European History Since 1789|last=Atkin|first=Nicholas|last2=Biddiss|first2=Michael|last3=Tallett|first3=Frank|date=2011-05-23|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-4443-9072-8|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=07iFBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA257|title=Revolutions Without Borders: The Call to Liberty in the Atlantic World|last=Polasky|first=Janet L.|date=2015|publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=978-0-300-20894-8|location=|pages=254|language=en}}</ref> [[Ferdinand I of the Two Sicilies|King Ferdinand]] fled from Naples to Sicily.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/cu31924070596782|title=The Cambridge Modern History|year=1902|last=|first=|publisher=CUP Archive|isbn=|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/cu31924070596782/page/n810 779]|language=en}}</ref> The [[French Directory]] had not authorized Championnet to establish a republic, and recalled him to France. The Republic then collapsed in June 1799.<ref name=\":7\" /> In an [[Invasion of Naples (1806)|1806 invasion]], [[Napoleon]], by then French Emperor, again dethroned King Ferdinand and appointed his brother, [[Joseph Bonaparte]], as King of Naples.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/josephbonaparte02abbogoog|quote=Naples (1806) Joseph Bonaparte.|title=Joseph Bonaparte|last=Abbott|first=John Stevens Cabot|date=1897|publisher=Harper|isbn=|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/josephbonaparte02abbogoog/page/n109 105]|language=en}}</ref> In the Edict of Bayonne of 1808 Napoleon moved Joseph to Spain and appointed their brother-in-law, [[Joachim Murat]], as King of the Two Sicilies, though this only meant control of the mainland portion of the kingdom.<ref name=\"colletta\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/historykingdomn04collgoog|quote=Edict of Bayonne.|title=History of the Kingdom of Naples (1858)|last=Colletta|first=Pietro|publisher=University of Michigan|year=1858}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/historykingdomn04collgoog|title=History of the kingdom of Naples: 1734-1825|last=Colletta|first=Pietro|date=1858|publisher=T. Constable and Co.|isbn=|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/historykingdomn04collgoog/page/n90 77]\u201378|language=en}}</ref> While Bonaparte and Murat were in power, Ferdinand remained in Sicily, with [[Palermo]] as his capital.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZTC3IWC_py8C&pg=PA291|title=The Congress of Vienna: A Study in Allied Unity, 1812-1822|last=Nicolson|first=Harold|date=2000|publisher=Grove Press|isbn=978-0-8021-3744-9|location=|pages=291|language=en}}</ref> \n\nMurat remained in power and joined the [[Sixth Coalition]] against Napoleon in 1813. The coalition resulted in the defeat of Napoleon and his exile to [[Elba]]. When he escaped and took power for the [[Hundred Days]], Murat again sided with Napoleon. He was soon executed,<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N2WzDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA141|title=Napol\u00e9on Bonaparte: A Reference Guide to His Life and Works|last=Meeks|first=Joshua|date=2019-12-15|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=978-1-5381-1351-6|location=|pages=141|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://content.lib.washington.edu/napoleonweb/timeline.html|title=Napoleonic Period Collection|last=|first=|date=|website=Washington University Library|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref> and the [[Congress of Vienna]] restored Ferdinand in 1815.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=82N7DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA268|title=Italy in the Nineteenth Century: 1796-1900|last=Davis|first=John Anthony|date=2000|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-873128-3|location=|pages=268|language=en}}</ref> He established a [[concordat]] with the [[Papal States]], which previously had a claim to the land.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.murat.it/Libri/Bibliogafia%20della%20Valente.htm|title=Luigi de' Medici come uomo di stato e amministratore|last=Blanch|first=L|publisher=Archivio Storico per le Province Napoletane|access-date=4 April 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081024094834/http://www.murat.it/Libri/Bibliogafia%20della%20Valente.htm|archive-date=24 October 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>{{Better source|date=December 2019}}\n\n[[File:Murat2.jpg|thumb|left|145px|[[Joachim Murat]]]]\n[[file:Ritratto di Giuseppe Bonaparte.jpg|thumb|right|145px|[[Joseph Bonaparte]]]]\n\n=== Early history ===\nUnder Joseph Bonaparte and Joachim Murat, Naples had undergone many reforms. Bonaparte refused to impose the [[Continental System]] on the peninsula, which promoted stability in the region. Laws were standardized and cataloged, finances were balanced, taxes were reorganized, education was improved, and the government was consolidated into a [[civil administration]]. Though Murat had attempted to strengthen the military, when Ferdinand returned to power, the region was essentially defenseless.<ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite journal|last=Goodwin|first=John|date=1842|title=Progress of the Two Sicilies Under the Spanish Bourbons, from the Year 1734-35 to 1840|journal=Journal of the Statistical Society of London|volume=5|issue=1|pages=47\u201373|doi=10.2307/2337950|issn=0959-5341|jstor=2337950}}</ref>\n\n===Expedition of the Thousand===\n{{Main|Expedition of the Thousand}}\nBetween 1816 and 1848, the island of [[Sicily]] experienced three popular revolts against Bourbon rule, including the [[Sicilian revolution of independence of 1848|revolution of independence]] of 1848, when the island was fully independent of Bourbon control for 16 months. \n\nThe end of the kingdom came only with the [[Expedition of the Thousand]] in 1860, led by [[Giuseppe Garibaldi|Garibaldi]] \u2013 an icon of Italian unification \u2013 with the support of the [[House of Savoy]] and their [[Kingdom of Piedmont-Sardinia]]. The expedition resulted in a striking series of defeats for the Sicilian armies facing the growing troops of Garibaldi. After the capture of Palermo and Sicily, Garibaldi disembarked in [[Calabria]] and moved towards Naples, while in the meantime the Piedmontese also invaded the Kingdom from the [[Marche]]. The last battles took place at [[battle of Volturnus (1860)|Volturnus in 1860]] and at the [[siege of Gaeta (1860)|siege of Gaeta]], where King [[Francesco II of the Two Sicilies|Francis II]] (reigned 1859\u20131861) had sought shelter, hoping for French help, which never came. The last towns to resist Garibaldi's expedition, [[Messina]] and [[Civitella del Tronto]], capitulated on 13 March 1861 and on 20 March 1861 respectively. The Kingdom of the Two Sicilies dissolved and the new [[Kingdom of Italy (1861\u20131946)|Kingdom of Italy]], founded in the same year annexed its territory. {{citation needed|date=March 2015}} The fall of the Sicilian aristocracy in the face of Garibaldi's invasion forms the subject of the novel ''[[The Leopard]]'' by [[Giuseppe Tomasi di Lampedusa]] and its [[The Leopard (1963 film)|film adaptation]]. {{citation needed|date=March 2015}}\n\n== Historical population ==\n{| class=\"wikitable floatright\"\n!Year\n!Kingdom of Naples\n!Kingdom of Sicily\n!Total\n!Ref(s)\n|-\n|1819\n|5,733,430\n|{{Center|{{en dash}}}}\n|{{Center|{{en dash}}}}\n|<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/commercialstatis05macg|title=Commercial Statistics: A Digest of the Productive Resources, Commercial Legislation, Customs Tariffs, of All Nations. Including All British Commercial Treaties with Foreign States|last=Macgregor|first=John|date=1850|publisher=Whittaker and Company|isbn=|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/commercialstatis05macg/page/18 18]|language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n|1827\n|{{Center|{{en dash}}}}\n|{{Center|{{en dash}}}}\n|~7,420,000\n|<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TrcTAAAAQAAJ|title=The british cyclopedia of literature, history,geography, law ,and politics.|last=partington|first=charles F.|date=1836|publisher=|isbn=|location=|pages=553|language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n|1828\n|6,177,598\n|{{Center|{{en dash}}}}\n|{{Center|{{en dash}}}}\n|<ref name=\":0\" />\n|-\n|1832\n|{{Center|{{en dash}}}}\n|1,906,033\n|{{Center|{{en dash}}}}\n|<ref name=\":0\" />\n|-\n|1839\n|6,113,259\n|{{Center|{{en dash}}}}\n|~8,000,000\n|<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=X72YMqWnkSsC&pg=PA37|title=Italy in the Making 1815 to 1846|last=Berkeley|first=G. F.-H.|last2=Berkeley|first2=George Fitz-Hardinge|last3=Berkeley|first3=Joan|date=1968|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-07427-8|location=|pages=37|language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n|1840\n|6,117,598\n|~<1,800,000 (est.)\n|7,917,598\n|<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MrgTAAAAQAAJ&pg=PR18|title=Commercial Statistics: A Digest of the Productive Resources, Commercial Legislation, Customs Tariffs ... of All Nations ...|last=|first=|date=1844|publisher=C. Knight and Company|isbn=|location=|pages=18|language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n|1848\n|6,382,706\n|2,046,610\n|8,429,316\n|<ref name=\":1\" />\n|-\n|1851\n|6,612,892\n|2,041,583\n|8,704,472\n|<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zSNUAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA246|title=The Popular Encyclopedia: Or, Conversations Lexicon|last=|first=|date=1862|publisher=Blackie|isbn=|location=|pages=246|language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n|1856\n|6,886,030\n|2,231,020\n|9,117,050\n|<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P7lSAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA223|title=Selections from Speeches of Earl Russell 1817 to 1841 and from Despatches 1859 to 1865: With Introductions. In 2 Volumes|last=Russell|first=John|date=1870|publisher=Longmans, Green, and Company|isbn=|location=|pages=223|language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n|1859/60\n|6,986,906\n|2,294,373\n|9,281,279\n|<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=HARPAQAAIAAJ&q=%22The+total+population+of+the+continental+portion+of+the+Kingdom+was+6,986,906,+and+Sicily's+population+was+2,294,373.%22&dq=%22The+total+population+of+the+continental+portion+of+the+Kingdom+was+6,986,906,+and+Sicily's+population+was+2,294,373.%22|title=Mezzogiorno d'Europa|last=|first=|date=1983|publisher=|isbn=|location=|pages=473|language=en}}</ref>\n|}\nThe kingdom had a large population, at least three times as large as any other contemporary [[List of historic states of Italy|Italian state]]. At its peak, the kingdom had a [[military]] 100,000 soldiers strong, and a large [[bureaucracy]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1dlob9r5TH0C&pg=PA77|title=Structuring the State: The Formation of Italy and Germany and the Puzzle of Federalism|last=Ziblatt|first=Daniel|date=2008-01-21|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-1-4008-2724-4|location=|pages=77|language=en}}</ref> [[Naples]] was the largest city in the kingdom and the third largest city in Europe. The second largest city, [[Palermo]], was the third largest in Italy.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RVoSBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA125|title=Italy in the Age of the Risorgimento 1790 - 1870|last=Hearder|first=Harry|date=2014-07-22|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-87206-1|location=|pages=125\u20136|language=en}}</ref> In the 1800s, the kingdom experienced large population growth, rising from approximately five to seven million.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/betweensaltwater00tomm|url-access=registration|quote=kingdom of the two sicilies population.|title=Between Salt Water and Holy Water: A History of Southern Italy|last=Astarita|first=Tommaso|date=2006-07-17|publisher=W. W. Norton & Company|isbn=978-0-393-25432-7|language=en}}</ref> It held approximately 36% of Italy's population around 1850.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=m_vOBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA18|title=An Economic History of Liberal Italy (Routledge Revivals): 1850-1918|last=Toniolo|first=Gianni|date=2014-10-14|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-56953-4|location=|pages=18|language=en}}</ref>\n\nBecause the kingdom did not establish a statistical department until after 1848,<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=j-dXAAAAcAAJ&pg=RA1-PA19|title=House Documents|last=|first=|date=1870|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|isbn=|location=Washington, D.C.|pages=19|language=en}}</ref> most population statistics prior to that year are estimates and censuses undertaken were thought by contemporaries to be inaccurate.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n==Geography==\n\n===Departments===\n[[File:Suddivisione amministrativa del Regno delle Due Sicilie.png|thumb|350px|right|Departments and Districts of Kingdom of the Two Sicilies]]\n<!--Rider has a section on the talk page where it belongs-->\nThe peninsula was divided into fifteen departments<ref name=\":9\" /><ref>{{cite book|author=Pompilio Petitti|title= Repertorio amministrativo ossia collezione di leggi, decreti, reali rescritti ecc. sull'amministrazione civile del Regno delle Due Sicilie, vol. 1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gKRBAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA1|year=1851|publisher=Stabilimento Migliaccio|place=[[Napoli]]|page=1|language=Italian}}</ref> and Sicily was divided into seven departments.<ref>{{cite book|author=Pompilio Petitti|title=Repertorio amministrativo ossia collezione di leggi, decreti, reali rescritti ecc. sull'amministrazione civile del Regno delle Due Sicilie, vol. 1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gKRBAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA4|year=1851|publisher= Stabilimento Migliaccio|place=[[Napoli]]|page=4|language=Italian}}</ref> The island itself had a special administrative status, with its base at [[Palermo]].{{citation needed|date=March 2015}} In 1860, when the Two Sicilies were conquered by the [[Kingdom of Sardinia]], the departments became [[provinces of Italy]], according to the [[Rattazzi law]].{{citation needed|date=March 2015}}\n\n{|\n| valign=\"top\" |\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! \n! width=\"140px\" | Peninsula\n! width=\"210px\" | [[Capital (political)|Capital]]\n|-\n| 1\n| [[File:Coat of Arms of Abruzzo Ultra I (last version).svg|20px]] [[Abruzzo Ultra I]]\n| [[Teramo]]\n|-\n| 2\n| [[File:Coat of Arms of Abruzzo Ultra (wings inverted).svg|20px]] [[Abruzzo Ultra II]]\n| [[L'Aquila|Aquila]]\n|-\n| 3\n| [[File:Coat of Arms of Abruzzo Citra.svg|20px]] [[Abruzzo Citra]]\n| [[Chieti]]\n|-\n| 4\n| [[File:Coat of Arms of Contado di Molise.svg|20px]] [[Contado di Molise]]\n| [[Campobasso]]\n|-\n| 5\n| [[File:Coat of Arms of Terra di Lavoro.svg|20px]] [[Terra di Lavoro]]\n| [[Capua]],<br />[[Caserta]] from 1818 \n|-\n| 6\n| [[File:Coat of Arms of the Province of Naples (historical province).svg|20px]] {{nowrap|[[Province of Naples (1806\u20131860)|Province of Naples]]}}\n| [[Naples]]\n|-\n| 7\n| [[File:Coat of Arms of Principato Ultra.svg|20px]] [[Principato Ultra]]\n| [[Avellino]]{{efn|name=\"Benevento\"}}\n|-\n| 8\n| [[File:Coat of Arms of Principato Citra.svg|20px]] [[Principato Citra]]\n| [[Salerno]]\n|-\n| 9\n| [[File:Coat of Arms of Capitanata.svg|20px]] [[Capitanata]]\n| {{nowrap|originally [[San Severo]],}} {{nowrap|then [[Foggia]]}}\n|-\n| 10\n| [[File:Coat of Arms of Terra di Bari.svg|20px]] [[Terra di Bari]]\n| [[Bari]]\n|-\n| 11\n| [[File:Coat of Arms of Terra d'Otranto.svg|20px]] [[Terra d'Otranto]]\n| [[Lecce]]\n|-\n| 12\n| [[File:Coat of Arms of Basilicata.svg|20px]] [[Basilicata]]\n| [[Potenza]]\n|-\n| 13\n| [[File:Coat of Arms of Calabria Citra.svg|20px]] [[Calabria Citra]]\n| [[Cosenza]]\n|-\n| 14\n| [[File:Coat of Arms of Calabria Ultra.svg|20px]] [[Calabria Ultra II]]\n| [[Catanzaro]]\n|-\n| 15\n| [[File:Coat of Arms of the Province of Reggio-Calabria.svg|20px]] [[Calabria Ultra I]]\n| [[Reggio Calabria|Reggio]]\n|-\n|}\n| width=\"30\" | &nbsp;\n| valign=\"top\" |\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! \n! width=\"140px\" | Insular\n! width=\"210px\" | [[Capital (political)|Capital]]\n|-\n| 16\n| [[File:Caltanissetta-Stemma.png|20px]] [[Province of Caltanissetta (Kingdom of Two Sicilies)|Caltanissetta]]\n| [[Caltanissetta]]\n|-\n| 17\n| [[File:Provincia di Catania-Stemma.svg|20px]] [[Province of Catania (Kingdom of Two Sicilies)|Catania]]\n| [[Catania]]\n|-\n| 18\n| [[Province of Girgenti|Girgenti]]\n| [[Agrigento|Girgenti]]\n|-\n| 19\n|  [[Province of Messina (Kingdom of Two Sicilies)|Messina]]\n| [[Messina]]\n|-\n| 20\n| [[Province of Noto|Noto]]\n| [[Noto]]\n|-\n| 21\n| [[Province of Palermo (Kingdom of Two Sicilies)|Palermo]]\n| [[Palermo]]\n|-\n| 22\n| [[Province of Trapani (Kingdom of Two Sicilies)|Trapani]]\n| [[Trapani]]\n|}\n|}\n{{notelist|refs=\n{{efn|name=\"Benevento\"|The city of [[Benevento]] was formally included in this department, but it was occupied by the [[Papal States]] and was de facto an [[exclave]] of that country.{{citation needed|date=March 2015}}}}\n}}\n\n==Economy==\n{{More citations needed section|date=January 2020}}\n\n===Industry===\nIndustry was the largest source of income if compared with the other preunitarian states{{citation needed|date=August 2019}}. One of the most important industrial complexes in the kingdom was the [[shipyard]] of [[Castellammare di Stabia]], which employed 1800 workers. The engineering factory of [[Pietrarsa]] was the largest industrial plant in the Italian peninsula{{citation needed|date=August 2019}}, producing tools, [[cannon]]s, rails, [[locomotive]]s. The complex also included a school for train drivers, and naval engineers and, thanks to this school, the kingdom was able to replace the English personnel who had been necessary until then. The first [[steamboat]] with [[propellor|screw propulsion]] known in the Mediterranean Sea was the \"Giglio delle Onde\", with mail delivery and passenger transport purposes after 1847.\n\nIn Calabria, the Fonderia Ferdinandea was a large [[foundry]] where cast iron was produced. The [[Reali ferriere ed Officine di Mongiana]] was an iron foundry and [[weapon]]s factory. Founded in 1770, it employed 1600 workers in 1860 and closed in 1880.  In Sicily (near [[Catania]] and [[Agrigento]]), [[sulfur]] was mined to make [[gunpowder]]. The Sicilian mines were able to satisfy most of the global demand for sulfur. [[Silk]] cloth production was focused in [[San Leucio]] (near [[Caserta]]). The region of [[Basilicata]] also had several mills in [[Potenza]] and [[San Chirico Raparo]], where [[cotton]], [[wool]] and silk were processed.  [[food industry|Food processing]] was widespread, especially near [[Naples]] ([[Torre Annunziata]] and [[Gragnano]]).<!-- Deleted because just too incredible and unsourced. Reinstate if a source can be produced: \"Almost 99% of the industries present in the Kingdom were destroyed and relocated to the north by the occupying forces of the [[House of Savoy]] after the unification.\" --> \n\n==== Sulfur ====\n{{Main|Sulphur Crisis of 1840}}\nThe kingdom maintained a large [[sulfur]] mining industry. In [[Industrial Revolution|industrializing]] Britain, with the repeal of [[Tariff|tariffs]] on salt in 1824, demand for sulfur from Sicily surged upward. The increasing British control and exploitation of the mining, refining, and transportation of the sulfur, coupled with the failure of this lucrative export to transform Sicily's backward and impoverished economy, led to the 'Sulfur Crisis' of 1840, when [[Ferdinand II of the Two Sicilies|King Ferdinand II]] gave a monopoly of the sulfur industry to a French firm, violating an earlier 1816 trade agreement with Britain. A peaceful solution was eventually negotiated by France.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Thomson|first1=D. W.|date=April 1995|title=Prelude to the Sulphur War of 1840: The Neapolitan Perspective|journal=European History Quarterly|volume=25|issue=2|pages=163\u2013180|doi=10.1177/026569149502500201}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=wZg4ecXXmNYC|title=Sicily and the Unification of Italy: Liberal Policy and Local Power, 1859\u20131866|author=Riall, Lucy|date=1998|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780191542619|accessdate=7 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Transport===\n[[File:Italia ferrovie 1861.03.17.png|thumb|Rail lines of the Italian Peninsula in 1861]]\n[[File:Italia ferrovie 1870 09 20.png|thumb|Rail lines in Italy in 1870]]\nWith all of its major cities boasting successful ports{{citation needed|date=August 2019}}, transport and trade in the Kingdom of the Two Sicilies was most efficiently conducted by sea. The Kingdom possessed the largest merchant fleet in the Mediterranean. Urban road conditions were to the best European standards{{citation needed|date=August 2019}}, by 1839, the main streets of Naples were gas-lit. Efforts were made to tackle the tough mountainous terrain, Ferdinand II built the cliff-top road along the Sorrentine peninsula. Road conditions in the interior and hinterland areas of the kingdom made internal trade difficult. The first railways and iron-suspension bridges in Italy were developed in the south, as was the first overland electric telegraph cable{{citation needed|date=August 2019}}.\n\n===Technological and scientific achievements===\nThe kingdom achieved several scientific and technological accomplishments, such as the first steamboat in the Mediterrean Sea (1818),<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=HDNXAAAAYAAJ&q=%22the+Bourbon+kingdom+of+the+Two+Sicilies+boasted+a+stake+in+shipbuilding,+textiles+and+railway+engines.TheMediterranean's+first+steamboat+was+launched+from+Naples+in+1818.%22&dq=%22the+Bourbon+kingdom+of+the+Two+Sicilies+boasted+a+stake+in+shipbuilding,+textiles+and+railway+engines.TheMediterranean's+first+steamboat+was+launched+from+Naples+in+1818.%22|title=The Economist|last=|first=|date=1975|publisher=Economist Newspaper Limited|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=aYcUQ4XRqOoC&pg=PA20&dq=Mediterranean's+first+steamboat+%221818%22#v=onepage&q=Mediterranean's%20first%20steamboat%20%221818%22&f=false|title=Naval Warfare, 1815-1914|last=Sondhaus|first=Lawrence|date=2012-10-12|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-60994-9|location=|pages=20|language=en}}</ref> built in the shipyard of Stanislao Filosa al ponte di Vigliena, near Naples,{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}} and the first [[railway]] in the Italian peninsula (1839), which [[Naples\u2013Portici railway|connected Naples to Portici]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.historytoday.com/archive/la-dolce-vita-italy-rail-1839-1914|title=La Dolce Vita? Italy By Rail, 1839-1914 {{!}} History Today|last=|first=|date=|website=History Today|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref> However, until the Italian unification, the railway development was highly limited. In the year 1859, the kingdom had only 99 kilometers of rail, compared to the 850 kilometers of [[Kingdom of Piedmont-Sardinia|Piedmont]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/concisehistoryof00dugg|url-access=registration|title=A Concise History of Italy|last=Duggan|first=Christopher|date=1994|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-40848-6|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/concisehistoryof00dugg/page/152 152]|language=en}}</ref> This was because the kingdom could count on a very large and efficient merchant navy, which was able to compensate for the need for railways. Also, southern landscape was mainly mountainous making the process of building railways quite difficult, as building railway tunnels was much harder at the time.{{citation needed|date=August 2019}} Other achievements included the first volcano observatory in the world, [[Vesuvius Observatory|l'Osservatorio Vesuviano]] (1841),<ref>{{Cite journal|last=De Lucia|first=Maddalena|last2=Ottaiano|first2=Mena|last3=Limoncelli|first3=Bianca|last4=Parlato|first4=Luigi|last5=Scala|first5=Omar|last6=Siviglia|first6=Vittoria|date=2010|title=The Museum of Vesuvius Observatory and its public. Years 2005 - 2008|journal=EGUGA|language=en|volume=|pages=2942|bibcode=2010EGUGA..12.2942D}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/2009/06/volcano-profile-mt-vesuvius/|title=Volcano Profile: Mt. Vesuvius|last=Klemetti|first=Erik|date=2009-06-07|work=Wired|access-date=2019-12-29|issn=1059-1028}}</ref>. The rails for the first Italian railways were built in Mongiana as well. All the rails of the old railways that went from the south to as far as [[Bologna]] were built in Mongiana. {{citation needed|date=March 2015}}\n\n==Monarchy==\n\n===Kings of the Two Sicilies===\n{{Main|Monarchs of the Two Sicilies|Monarchs of Sicily|Monarchs of Naples}}\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Ferdinand i twosicilies.jpg|[[Ferdinand I of the Two Sicilies|Ferdinand I]], 1816\u20131825\nFile:Francis I of the Two Sicilies.jpg|[[Francis I of the Two Sicilies|Francis I]], 1825\u20131830\nFile:Fernando II de las Dos Sicilias 2.jpg|[[Ferdinand II of the Two Sicilies|Ferdinand II]], 1830\u20131859\nFile:Ignoto, Ritratto di Francesco II, 1859. Caserta, Palazzo Reale.jpg|[[Francis II of the Two Sicilies|Francis II]], 1859\u20131861\n</gallery>\nIn 1860\u201361 with influence from Great Britain and [[Gladstone's]] propaganda, the kingdom was absorbed into the [[Kingdom of Sardinia]], and the title dropped. It is still claimed by the head of the [[House of Bourbon-Two Sicilies]].\n\n===Titles of King of the Two Sicilies===\nFrancis I or Francis II, King of the Two Sicilies, of [[King of Jerusalem|Jerusalem]], etc., [[Duchy of Parma|Duke of Parma]], Piacenza, [[Duchy of Castro|Castro]], etc., Hereditary Grand Prince of Tuscany, etc.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FsXEdzv7ZzIC&pg=PA250|title=Treaties and Other International Acts of the United States of America: Documents 173-200: 1855-1858|last=States|first=United|date=1931|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|isbn=|location=|pages=250|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==House of Bourbon in exile==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=April 2018}}\nSome sovereigns continued to maintain diplomatic relations with the exiled court, including the [[Franz Joseph I of Austria|Emperor of Austria]], the Kings of Bavaria, W\u00fcrttemberg and Hanover, the Queen of Spain, the [[Alexander II of Russia|Emperor of Russia]], and the Papacy. {{When|date=March 2015}}\n\n==Flags of the Kingdom of the Two Sicilies==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=April 2018}}\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nImage:Flag of the Kingdom of the Two Sicilies (1738).svg|1816\u20131848; 1849\u20131860 flag\nImage:Flag of the Kingdom of the Two Sicilies (1848).svg|1848\u20131849 flag\nImage:Flag of the Kingdom of the Two Sicilies (1860).svg|1860\u20131861 flag\n</gallery>\n\n[[File:Arms of the flag of two sicilies.png|center|thumb|600px|Description of the arms appearing in the flag.  Corrections: the upper part of the block marked \"[[Flanders]]\" is Burgundy Ancient; Burgundy Modern (as it is called in English; shown here as New Burgundy) includes a red-and-white border; the block marked \"Aragon Two Sicilies\" is only for Sicily proper (the other \"Sicily\" being the Angevin kingdom of Naples).]]\n\n==Orders of knighthood==\n*[[Order of St. Januarius]]\n*[[Sacred Military Constantinian Order of Saint George]]\n*[[Order of Saint George and Reunion]]\n*[[Order of Saint Ferdinand and Merit]]\n*[[Royal Order of Francis I]]\n\n==Further reading==\n*''[[The Volcano Lover]]'', a novel by [[Susan Sontag]], is set in the Kingdom of the Two Sicilies during the Napoleonic era.\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Italy}}\n* [[Dictatorship of Garibaldi]]\n* [[List of historic states of Italy]]\n* [[List of monarchs of the Kingdom of the Two Sicilies]]\n* [[Southern Italy]]\n* [[Southern Italy autonomist movements]]\n* [[Two Sicilies national football team]]\n* [[Army of the Two Sicilies]]\n* [[Real Marina (Kingdom of the Two Sicilies)]]\n* [[Line of succession to the former throne of the Kingdom of the Two Sicilies]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Alio, Jacqueline. ''Sicilian Studies: A Guide and Syllabus for Educators'' (2018), 250 pp.\n* Eckaus, Richard S. \"The North-South differential in Italian economic development.\" ''Journal of Economic History'' (1961) 21#3 pp: 285\u2013317.\n* Finley, M. I., Denis Mack Smith and Christopher Duggan, '' A History of Sicily'' (1987) abridged one-volume version of 3-volume set of 1969)\n* Imbruglia, Girolamo, ed. ''Naples in the eighteenth century: The birth and death of a nation state'' (Cambridge University Press, 2000)\n* Petrusewicz, Marta. \"Before the Southern Question: 'Native' Ideas on Backwardness and Remedies in the Kingdom of Two Sicilies, 1815\u20131849.\" in ''Italy's 'Southern Question''' (Oxford: Berg, 1998) pp: 27\u201350.\n* Pinto, Carmine. \"The 1860 disciplined Revolution. The Collapse of the Kingdom of the Two Sicilies.\" ''Contemporanea'' (2013) 16#1 pp: 39\u201368.\n* Riall, Lucy. ''Sicily and the Unification of Italy: Liberal Policy & Local Power, 1859\u20131866'' (1998), 252pp\n* Zamagni, Vera. ''The economic history of Italy 1860\u20131990'' (Oxford University Press, 1993)\n\n==External links==\n*{{in lang|it}} [http://www.ilportaledelsud.org/ Brigantino \u2013 Il portale del Sud], a massive Italian-language site dedicated to the history, culture and arts of southern Italy\n*{{in lang|it}} [http://www.editorialeilgiglio.it/ Casa Editoriale Il Giglio], an Italian publisher that focuses on history, culture and the arts in the Two Sicilies\n*{{in lang|it}} [http://www.vocedimegaride.it/ La Voce di Megaride], a website by Marina Salvadore dedicated to Napoli and Southern Italy\n*{{in lang|it}} [http://www.angelomanna.it/ Associazione culturale \"Amici di Angelo Manna\"], dedicated to the work of <!--?: volcanic--> Angelo Manna, historian, poet and deputy\n*{{in lang|it}} [http://www.eleaml.altervista.org/index.html Fora! The e-journal of Nicola Zitara], professor; includes many articles about southern Italy's culture and history\n*[http://www.regalis.com/ Regalis], a website on Italian dynastic history, with sections on the House of the Two Sicilies\n\n\n{{The Bourbons of Naples and Sicily (1735\u20131816)}}\n{{Kings and Princes of the Two Sicilies}}\n{{Sicily}}\n{{Former monarchies Italian peninsula}}\n{{Former Monarchies}}\n{{Risorgimento}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kingdom of the Two Sicilies}}\n[[Category:Kingdom of the Two Sicilies| ]]\n[[Category:House of Bourbon-Two Sicilies| ]]\n[[Category:History of Sicily]]\n[[Category:History of Campania]]\n[[Category:History of Calabria]]\n[[Category:History of Apulia]]\n[[Category:History of Basilicata]]\n[[Category:Italian unification]]\n[[Category:Rival successions|Two Sicilies]]\n[[Category:States and territories established in 1816]]\n[[Category:1816 establishments in the Kingdom of the Two Sicilies]]\n[[Category:1861 disestablishments in the Kingdom of the Two Sicilies]]\n[[Category:Christian states|Two Sicilies]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{short description|Italian state (pre-unification)}}\n{{Infobox country\n| native_name                = {{native name|it|Regno delle Due Sicilie}}<br/>{{native name|nap|Regno d\u2019\u2019e Doje Sicilie}}<br/>{{native name|scn|Regnu d\u00ee Dui Sicili}}\n| conventional_long_name                = Kingdom of the Two Sicilies\n| common_name                = Two Sicilies||\n| life_span                = 1816\u20131861\n| event_pre                = Edict of [[Bayonne]]<ref>{{cite book|author=Pietro Colletta|title=History of the kingdom of Naples: 1734\u20131825|url=https://archive.org/details/historykingdomn04collgoog|year=1858|publisher=T. Constable and Co.|page=[https://archive.org/details/historykingdomn04collgoog/page/n184 71]}}</ref><ref>[http://bp3.blogger.com/_24klMrIuq58/Rl6iFe3-oZI/AAAAAAAAANE/Ys2vdy9W3rA/s1600-h/Murat1.jpg. Proclaims with Murat's title]. {{in lang|it}}</ref>\n| event_start                = Edict of [[Ferdinand I of the Two Sicilies|Ferdinand IV of Naples]]\n| year_start                = 12 December 1816\n| event1                = [[Expedition of the Thousand|Garibaldi's landing in Sicily]]\n| date_event1                = 5 May 1860\n| event_end                = [[Italian unification|Declaration of Unification]]\n| year_end                = 17 March 1861|\n| p1                = Kingdom of Sicily\n| flag_p1                = Bandiera del Regno di Sicilia 4.svg\n| p2                = Kingdom of Naples\n| flag_p2                = Bandera de N%C3%A1poles - Trast%C3%A1mara.svg\n| s1                = Kingdom of Italy\n| flag_s1                = Flag of Italy (1861-1946) crowned.svg|\n| image_flag                = Flag of the Kingdom of the Two Sicilies (1738).svg\n| flag_type                = [[Kingdom of the Two Sicilies#Flags of the Kingdom of the Two Sicilies|Flag<br>(1816\u20131848; 1849\u20131860)]]\n| image_coat                = Great Royal Coat of Arms of theTwo Sicilies.svg\n| image_map                = Kingdom_of_the_Two_Sicilies_within_Europe_in_1839.svg\n| image_map_caption                = Location of the '''Kingdom of the Two Sicilies''' within Europe in 1839|\n| capital                = [[Palermo]] {{Small|(1816\u20131817)}}<br>[[Naples]] {{Small|(1817\u20131861)}}\n| national_motto                = \n| national_anthem                = \"[[Inno al Re]]\"<br><small>(\"Hymn to the King\")</small><center>[[File:Giovanni Paisiello - Inno al Re \u2014 Inno nazionale del Regno delle Due Sicilie.ogg]]</center>\n| common_languages                = [[Neapolitan language|Neapolitan]]<br/>[[Sicilian language|Sicilian]]<br/>[[Italian language|Italian]]<br/>[[Molise Croatian]]<br/>[[Gallo-Italic of Sicily]]<br/>[[Gallo-Italic of Basilicata]]<br/>[[Franco-Proven\u00e7al language|Franco-Proven\u00e7al]]<br/>[[Occitan language|Occitan]]<br/>[[Griko language|Griko]]<br/>[[Calabrian Greek|Greek-Bovesian]]<br/>[[Arberesh language|Arberesh]]\n| religion                = [[Roman Catholicism]]\n| currency                = [[Two Sicilies ducat]]\n| government_type                = [[Absolute monarchy]]<br>{{Small|(1816\u20131848; 1849\u20131861)}}<br>[[Constitutional monarchy]]<br>{{Small|(1848\u20131849)}}\n| title_leader                = [[List of monarchs of the Two Sicilies|King]]\n| leader1                = [[Ferdinand I of the Two Sicilies|Ferdinand I]] {{Small|(first)}}\n| year_leader1                = 1816\u20131825\n| leader2                = [[Francis II of the Two Sicilies|Francis II]] {{Small|(last)}}\n| year_leader2                = 1859\u20131861\n| today                = [[Italy]]<br />[[Croatia]]{{anchor|infoa}}<sup>[[#inforefa|[a]]]</sup>\n| footnotes                = {{anchor|inforefa}}a. '''[[#infoa|^]]''' The archipelago of [[Palagru\u017ea]] was part of the province of Capitanata.\n| demonym                = \n| area_km2                = \n| area_rank                = \n| GDP_PPP                = \n| GDP_PPP_year                = \n| HDI                = \n| HDI_year                = \n| population_estimate                = 9,281,279 (1859/60)\n}}\n\n{{More citations needed|date=April 2018}}{{About|the kingdom from 1816 to 1860|the kingdom from 1130 to 1282|Kingdom of Sicily}}\n\nThe '''Kingdom of the Two Sicilies''' ({{lang-nap|Regno d\u2019\u2019e Ddoje Sicilie}}; {{lang-scn|Regnu d\u00ee Dui Sicili}}; {{lang-it|Regno delle Due Sicilie}}; {{lang-es|Reino de las Dos Sicilias}})<ref>{{Cite book|last=Swinburne|first=Henry |authorlink = Henry Swinburne|title=Travels in the Two Sicilies (1790)|publisher=British Library|url=https://archive.org/details/travelsintwosic00swingoog|quote=two sicilies.|year=1790 }}</ref> was a kingdom located in [[Southern Italy]] from 1816\u20131860.<ref>{{Cite book|last=De Sangro |first= Michele |title= I Borboni nel Regno delle Due Sicilie |year= 2003 |publisher= Edizioni Caponi |location= Lecce |language=it}}</ref> The kingdom was the largest sovereign state by population and size in [[Italy]] prior to [[Italian unification]], comprising Sicily and all of [[Italian Peninsula|Peninsula Italy]] south of the [[Papal States]], covering most of the area of today's [[Mezzogiorno]].\n\nThe kingdom was formed when the [[Kingdom of Sicily]] merged with the [[Kingdom of Naples]], which was officially known as the Kingdom of Sicily. Since both kingdoms were named Sicily, they were collectively known as the \"Two Sicilies\" (''Utraque Sicilia'', literally \"both Sicilies\"), and the unified kingdom adopted this name. The King of the Two Sicilies was [[Expedition of the Thousand|overthrown by Giuseppe Garibaldi]] in 1860, after which the people voted in a [[plebiscite]] to join the [[House of Savoy|Savoyard]] [[Kingdom of Sardinia]]. The annexation of the Two Sicilies completed the first phase of [[Italian unification]], and the new [[Kingdom of Italy (1861\u20131946)|Kingdom of Italy]] was proclaimed in 1861.\n\nThe Two Sicilies were heavily agricultural, like the other Italian states.<ref>{{cite web|author=Nicola Zitara|url=http://www.eleaml.org/e_book/unitruff_cap1.pdf|title=La legge di Archimede: L'accumulazione selvaggia nell'Italia unificata e la nascita del colonialismo interno|publisher=Eleaml-Fora!|language=Italian}}{{dead link|date=December 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\n==Name==\nThe name \"Two Sicilies\" originated from the partition of the medieval [[Kingdom of Sicily]]. Until 1285, the island of [[Sicily]] and the [[Mezzogiorno]] were constituent parts of the Kingdom of Sicily. As a result of the [[War of the Sicilian Vespers]] (1282\u20131302),<ref name=\"dieli\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.dieli.net/SicilyPage/History/SicilianHist.html|publisher=Dieli.net|title=Sicilian History|date=7 October 2007}}</ref> the King of Sicily lost the Island of Sicily (also called Trinacria) to the [[Crown of Aragon]], but remained ruler over the peninsular part of the realm. Although his territory became known unofficially as the [[Kingdom of Naples]], he and his successors never gave up the title \"King of Sicily\" and still officially referred to their realm as the \"Kingdom of Sicily\". At the same time, the Aragonese rulers of the Island of Sicily also called their realm the \"Kingdom of Sicily\". Thus, there were two kingdoms called \"Sicily\":<ref name=\"dieli\" /> hence, the '''Two Sicilies'''.\n\n==Background==\n\n===Origins of the two kingdoms===\n{{Main|Kingdom of Sicily|Kingdom of Naples}}\n[[File:Chapelle Palatine.jpg|thumb|150px|[[Cappella Palatina]], church of first unifier [[Roger II of Sicily]].]]\nIn 1130 the [[Normans|Norman]] king [[Roger II of Sicily|Roger II]] formed the [[Kingdom of Sicily]] by combining the [[County of Sicily]] with the southern part of the Italian Peninsula (then known as the [[Duchy of Apulia and Calabria]]) as well as with the [[Maltese Islands]]. The capital of this kingdom was [[Palermo]]&nbsp;\u2014 which is on the island of [[Sicily]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Oldfield|first=Paul|date=2017|title=Alexander of Telese's Encomium of Capua and the Formation of the Kingdom of Sicily|url=https://www.research.manchester.ac.uk/portal/files/47249890/Oldfield_History_revised_.pdf|url-status=live|journal=[[History (journal)|History]]|volume=|pages=183\u2013200|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190427101137/https://www.research.manchester.ac.uk/portal/files/47249890/Oldfield_History_revised_.pdf|archive-date=April 27, 2019|via=}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Oldfield|first=Paul|chapter=Italo-Norman Empire|date=2015|encyclopedia=The Encyclopedia of Empire|volume=|pages=1\u20133|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|language=en|doi=10.1002/9781118455074.wbeoe004|isbn=978-1-118-45507-4|title=The Encyclopedia of Empire: A-C}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/place/Kingdom-of-the-Two-Sicilies|title=Kingdom of the Two Sicilies {{!}} historical kingdom, Italy|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref>\n\nDuring the reign of [[Charles I of Naples|Charles I]] of [[Capetian House of Anjou|Anjou]] (1266\u20131285),<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Ij0rDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA3|title=The Clement Bible at the Medieval Courts of Naples and Avignon: \"A Story of Papal Power, Royal Prestige, and Patronage \"|last=Fleck|first=CathleenA|date=2017-07-05|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-351-54553-2|location=|pages=3|language=en}}</ref> the [[War of the Sicilian Vespers]] (1282\u20131302) split the kingdom.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Shneidman|first=J. Lee|date=1960|title=Aragon and the War of the Sicilian Vespers|journal=The Historian|volume=22|issue=3|pages=250\u2013263|issn=0018-2370|jstor=24437629|doi=10.1111/j.1540-6563.1960.tb01657.x}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=qTDfAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA449|title=Dictionary of Wars|last=Kohn|first=George Childs|date=2013-10-31|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-135-95494-9|location=|pages=449|language=en}}</ref> Charles, who was of French origin, lost the island of Sicily to the [[House of Barcelona]], who were from [[Crown of Aragon|Aragon]] and [[Catalan people|Catalan]].<ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=E2CTAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT1063|title=Medieval Italy: An Encyclopedia|last=Kleinhenz|first=Christopher|date=2004-08-02|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-135-94880-1|location=|pages=1103|language=en}}</ref>  Charles remained king of the peninsular region, which became informally known as the [[Kingdom of Naples]]. Officially Charles never gave up the title of \"The Kingdom of Sicily\", thus there existed two separate kingdoms calling themselves \"Sicily\".<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=0fwxAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA63|title=Southern Italy in the Late Middle Ages: Demographic, Institutional and Economic Change in the Kingdom of Naples, c.1440-c.1530|last=Sakellariou|first=Eleni|date=2011-12-09|publisher=BRILL|isbn=978-90-04-22405-6|location=|pages=63|language=en}}</ref>\n\n===Aragonese and Spanish direct rule===\n{{Main|Crown of Aragon|Spanish Empire}}\n[[File:Imperi de la Corona d'Arag\u00f3.png|thumb|left|180px|Crown of Aragon, greatest extent]]\nOnly with the [[Peace of Caltabellotta]] (1302), sponsored by [[Pope Boniface VIII]], did the two kings of \"Sicily\" recognize each other's legitimacy; the island kingdom then became the \"[[Kingdom of Trinacria]]\" in official contexts,<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TNs3BQAAQBAJ&pg=PT847|title=Medieval Italy: An Encyclopedia|last=Kleinhenz|first=Christopher|date=2004-08-02|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-135-94879-5|location=|pages=847|language=en}}</ref> though the populace still called it Sicily.<ref name=\"dieli\"/>{{Better source|date=December 2019}} In 1442, [[Alfonso V of Aragon]], king of insular Sicily, conquered Naples and became king of both.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xVMJAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT716|title=A History of Medieval Spain|last=O'Callaghan|first=Joseph F.|date=2013-11-12|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=978-0-8014-6871-1|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CcfzAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA19|title=The Italians|last=Hooper|first=John|date=2015-01-29|publisher=Penguin|isbn=978-0-698-18364-3|location=|pages=19|language=en}}</ref>\n\nAlfonso V called his kingdom in [[Latin]] \"''Regnum Utriusque Sicili\u00e6\"'', meaning \"Kingdom of both Sicilies\".<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nZm3Mj9yRJYC&pg=PT210|title=Vanished Kingdoms: The Rise and Fall of States and Nations|last=Davies|first=Norman|date=2012-01-05|publisher=Penguin|isbn=978-1-101-54534-8|location=|pages=210|language=en}}</ref> At the death of Alfonso in 1458, the kingdom again became divided between his brother [[John II of Aragon]], who kept the island of Sicily, and his illegitimate son [[Ferdinand I of Naples|Ferdinand]], who became King of Naples.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/encyclopaediabri13kell|title=The Encyclopaedia Britannica: latest edition. A dictionary of arts, sciences and general literature|last=Kellogg|first=Day Otis|last2=Smith|first2=William Robertson|date=1902|publisher=Werner|isbn=|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/encyclopaediabri13kell/page/478 478]|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":2\" /> In 1501, King [[Ferdinand II of Aragon]], the son of John II, agreed to help [[Louis XII of France]] conquer Naples and [[Milan]]. After [[Frederick of Naples|Frederick IV]] was forced to abdicate, the French took power, and Louis reigned as Louis III of Naples for three years. Negotiations to divide the region failed, and the French soon began unsuccessful attempts to force the Spanish out of the peninsula.<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1LCJDAAAQBAJ&pg=PA151|title=The Spanish Empire: A Historical Encyclopedia [2 volumes]: A Historical Encyclopedia|last=Tarver|first=H. Micheal|last2=Slape|first2=Emily|date=2016-07-25|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-61069-422-3|location=|pages=151|language=en}}</ref> \n\nAfter the French lost the [[Battle of Garigliano (1503)|Battle of Garigliano]] (1503), they left the kingdom. Ferdinand II then re-united the two areas into one kingdom.<ref name=\":4\" /> From 1516, when [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor]] became the first [[King of Spain]], both Naples and Sicily came under direct Spanish rule.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.britannica.com/place/Italy|title=Italy - The age of Charles V|website=Encyclopedia Britannica|language=en|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref> In 1530 Charles V granted the islands of [[Malta]] and [[Gozo]], which had been part of the Kingdom of Sicily, to the [[Knights Hospitaller]] (thereafter known as the [[Order of Malta]]).<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/descriptionmalt03badggoog|title=Description of Malta and Gozo|last=Badger|first=George Percy|date=1838|publisher=M. Weiss|isbn=|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/descriptionmalt03badggoog/page/n39 19]\u201320|language=en}}</ref> At the end of the [[War of the Spanish Succession]], the [[Treaty of Utrecht]] in 1713 granted Sicily to the [[Duke of Savoy]],<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=nodOAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA426|title=Memoirs of the affairs of Europe from the Peace of Utrecht|last=|first=|date=1824|publisher=Murray|isbn=|location=|pages=426|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=lCJBDwAAQBAJ&pg=PT263|title=Britain, Spain and the Treaty of Utrecht 1713-2013|last=Dadson|first=Trevor J.|date=2017-12-02|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-351-19133-3|language=en}}</ref> until the [[Treaty of Rastatt]] in 1714 left Naples to the [[Charles VI, Holy Roman Emperor|Emperor Charles VI]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xhGFCgAAQBAJ&pg=PA207|title=Wars That Changed History: 50 of the World's Greatest Conflicts: 50 of the World's Greatest Conflicts|last=Tucker|first=Spencer C.|date=2015-09-22|publisher=ABC-CLIO|isbn=978-1-61069-786-6|location=|pages=270|language=en}}</ref> In the 1720 [[Treaty of The Hague (1720)|Treaty of The Hague]], the Emperor and Savoy exchanged Sicily for [[Sardinia]], thus reuniting Naples and Sicily.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=a_QLAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA670|title=Italy|last=Williams|first=Henry Smith|date=1907|work=The Times|isbn=|location=|pages=670|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4Joqn8mzOXwC&pg=PA121|title=Warfare on the Mediterranean in the Age of Sail: A History, 1571-1866|last=Blackmore|first=David S. T.|date=2014-01-10|publisher=McFarland|isbn=978-0-7864-5784-7|location=|pages=121|language=en}}</ref><!--<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xVMJAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT716|title=A History of Medieval Spain|last=O'Callaghan|first=Joseph F.|date=2013-11-12|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=978-0-8014-6871-1|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CcfzAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA19|title=The Italians|last=Hooper|first=John|date=2015-01-29|publisher=Penguin|year=|isbn=978-0-698-18364-3|location=|pages=19|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"waller\">Waller, Maureen. ''Sovereign Ladies: The Six Reigning Queens of England''. St. Martin's Press (New York), 2006. {{ISBN|0-312-33801-5}}.</ref>-->\n<!--<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xVMJAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT716|title=A History of Medieval Spain|last=O'Callaghan|first=Joseph F.|date=2013-11-12|publisher=Cornell University Press|isbn=978-0-8014-6871-1|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=CcfzAwAAQBAJ&pg=PA19|title=The Italians|last=Hooper|first=John|date=2015-01-29|publisher=Penguin|year=|isbn=978-0-698-18364-3|location=|pages=19|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\"waller\">Waller, Maureen. ''Sovereign Ladies: The Six Reigning Queens of England''. St. Martin's Press (New York), 2006. {{ISBN|0-312-33801-5}}.</ref>-->\n\n==History==\n\n===Unification of the Crowns===\n[[File:Ferdinand IV of Naples.jpg|thumb|140px|[[Ferdinand I of the Two Sicilies|Ferdinand I]]]]\n\nIn 1735, during the [[War of the Polish Succession]], [[Charles III of Spain|Charles, Duke of Parma]], defeated the occupying Austrians and became Charles III of Naples and Sicily.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Black|first=Jeremy|date=1986|title=British Neutrality in the War of the Polish Succession, 1733-1735|journal=The International History Review|volume=8|issue=3|pages=345\u2013366|issn=0707-5332|jstor=40105627|doi=10.1080/07075332.1986.9640416}}</ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Rm1e0nWo5N8C&pg=PA141|title=Italy: A Short History|last=Hearder|first=Harry|last2=Morris|first2=Jonathan|date=2001-12-13|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-00072-7|location=|pages=141, 143|language=en}}</ref> In 1759, Charles became King Carlos III of Spain and resigned Sicily and Naples to his younger son, who became [[Ferdinand III of Sicily]] and Ferdinand IV of Naples.<ref name=\":5\" /><ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://research.britishmuseum.org/research/search_the_collection_database/term_details.aspx?bioId=87575|title=Term details|website=British Museum|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref>\n\nIn January 1799, [[Jean-\u00c9tienne Championnet]], a general of the [[French First Republic]], captured Naples and proclaimed the [[Parthenopaean Republic]], a French client state, as successor to the kingdom.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1QyXCTW_MCQC&pg=PT670|title=The Wiley-Blackwell Dictionary of Modern European History Since 1789|last=Atkin|first=Nicholas|last2=Biddiss|first2=Michael|last3=Tallett|first3=Frank|date=2011-05-23|publisher=John Wiley & Sons|isbn=978-1-4443-9072-8|language=en}}</ref><ref name=\":7\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=07iFBwAAQBAJ&pg=PA257|title=Revolutions Without Borders: The Call to Liberty in the Atlantic World|last=Polasky|first=Janet L.|date=2015|publisher=Yale University Press|isbn=978-0-300-20894-8|location=|pages=254|language=en}}</ref> [[Ferdinand I of the Two Sicilies|King Ferdinand]] fled from Naples to Sicily.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/cu31924070596782|title=The Cambridge Modern History|year=1902|last=|first=|publisher=CUP Archive|isbn=|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/cu31924070596782/page/n810 779]|language=en}}</ref> The [[French Directory]] had not authorized Championnet to establish a republic, and recalled him to France. The Republic then collapsed in June 1799.<ref name=\":7\" /> In an [[Invasion of Naples (1806)|1806 invasion]], [[Napoleon]], by then French Emperor, again dethroned King Ferdinand and appointed his brother, [[Joseph Bonaparte]], as King of Naples.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/josephbonaparte02abbogoog|quote=Naples (1806) Joseph Bonaparte.|title=Joseph Bonaparte|last=Abbott|first=John Stevens Cabot|date=1897|publisher=Harper|isbn=|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/josephbonaparte02abbogoog/page/n109 105]|language=en}}</ref> In the Edict of Bayonne of 1808 Napoleon moved Joseph to Spain and appointed their brother-in-law, [[Joachim Murat]], as King of the Two Sicilies, though this only meant control of the mainland portion of the kingdom.<ref name=\"colletta\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/historykingdomn04collgoog|quote=Edict of Bayonne.|title=History of the Kingdom of Naples (1858)|last=Colletta|first=Pietro|publisher=University of Michigan|year=1858}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/historykingdomn04collgoog|title=History of the kingdom of Naples: 1734-1825|last=Colletta|first=Pietro|date=1858|publisher=T. Constable and Co.|isbn=|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/historykingdomn04collgoog/page/n90 77]\u201378|language=en}}</ref> While Bonaparte and Murat were in power, Ferdinand remained in Sicily, with [[Palermo]] as his capital.<ref name=\":6\" /><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZTC3IWC_py8C&pg=PA291|title=The Congress of Vienna: A Study in Allied Unity, 1812-1822|last=Nicolson|first=Harold|date=2000|publisher=Grove Press|isbn=978-0-8021-3744-9|location=|pages=291|language=en}}</ref> \n\nMurat remained in power and joined the [[Sixth Coalition]] against Napoleon in 1813. The coalition resulted in the defeat of Napoleon and his exile to [[Elba]]. When he escaped and took power for the [[Hundred Days]], Murat again sided with Napoleon. He was soon executed,<ref name=\":8\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=N2WzDwAAQBAJ&pg=PA141|title=Napol\u00e9on Bonaparte: A Reference Guide to His Life and Works|last=Meeks|first=Joshua|date=2019-12-15|publisher=Rowman & Littlefield|isbn=978-1-5381-1351-6|location=|pages=141|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://content.lib.washington.edu/napoleonweb/timeline.html|title=Napoleonic Period Collection|last=|first=|date=|website=Washington University Library|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-31}}</ref> and the [[Congress of Vienna]] restored Ferdinand in 1815.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=82N7DwAAQBAJ&pg=PA268|title=Italy in the Nineteenth Century: 1796-1900|last=Davis|first=John Anthony|date=2000|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=978-0-19-873128-3|location=|pages=268|language=en}}</ref> He established a [[concordat]] with the [[Papal States]], which previously had a claim to the land.<ref>{{Cite book|url=http://www.murat.it/Libri/Bibliogafia%20della%20Valente.htm|title=Luigi de' Medici come uomo di stato e amministratore|last=Blanch|first=L|publisher=Archivio Storico per le Province Napoletane|access-date=4 April 2008|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081024094834/http://www.murat.it/Libri/Bibliogafia%20della%20Valente.htm|archive-date=24 October 2008|url-status=dead}}</ref>{{Better source|date=December 2019}}\n\n[[File:Murat2.jpg|thumb|left|145px|[[Joachim Murat]]]]\n[[file:Ritratto di Giuseppe Bonaparte.jpg|thumb|right|145px|[[Joseph Bonaparte]]]]\n\n=== Early history ===\nUnder Joseph Bonaparte and Joachim Murat, Naples had undergone many reforms. Bonaparte refused to impose the [[Continental System]] on the peninsula, which promoted stability in the region. Laws were standardized and cataloged, finances were balanced, taxes were reorganized, education was improved, and the government was consolidated into a [[civil administration]]. Though Murat had attempted to strengthen the military, when Ferdinand returned to power, the region was essentially defenseless.<ref name=\":8\" /><ref name=\":9\">{{Cite journal|last=Goodwin|first=John|date=1842|title=Progress of the Two Sicilies Under the Spanish Bourbons, from the Year 1734-35 to 1840|journal=Journal of the Statistical Society of London|volume=5|issue=1|pages=47\u201373|doi=10.2307/2337950|issn=0959-5341|jstor=2337950}}</ref>\n\n===Expedition of the Thousand===\n{{Main|Expedition of the Thousand}}\nBetween 1816 and 1848, the island of [[Sicily]] experienced three popular revolts against Bourbon rule, including the [[Sicilian revolution of independence of 1848|revolution of independence]] of 1848, when the island was fully independent of Bourbon control for 16 months. \n\nThe end of the kingdom came only with the [[Expedition of the Thousand]] in 1860, led by [[Giuseppe Garibaldi|Garibaldi]] \u2013 an icon of Italian unification \u2013 with the support of the [[House of Savoy]] and their [[Kingdom of Piedmont-Sardinia]]. The expedition resulted in a striking series of defeats for the Sicilian armies facing the growing troops of Garibaldi. After the capture of Palermo and Sicily, Garibaldi disembarked in [[Calabria]] and moved towards Naples, while in the meantime the Piedmontese also invaded the Kingdom from the [[Marche]]. The last battles took place at [[battle of Volturnus (1860)|Volturnus in 1860]] and at the [[siege of Gaeta (1860)|siege of Gaeta]], where King [[Francesco II of the Two Sicilies|Francis II]] (reigned 1859\u20131861) had sought shelter, hoping for French help, which never came. The last towns to resist Garibaldi's expedition, [[Messina]] and [[Civitella del Tronto]], capitulated on 13 March 1861 and on 20 March 1861 respectively. The Kingdom of the Two Sicilies dissolved and the new [[Kingdom of Italy (1861\u20131946)|Kingdom of Italy]], founded in the same year annexed its territory. {{citation needed|date=March 2015}} The fall of the Sicilian aristocracy in the face of Garibaldi's invasion forms the subject of the novel ''[[The Leopard]]'' by [[Giuseppe Tomasi di Lampedusa]] and its [[The Leopard (1963 film)|film adaptation]]. {{citation needed|date=March 2015}}\n\n== Historical population ==\n{| class=\"wikitable floatright\"\n!Year\n!Kingdom of Naples\n!Kingdom of Sicily\n!Total\n!Ref(s)\n|-\n|1819\n|5,733,430\n|{{Center|{{en dash}}}}\n|{{Center|{{en dash}}}}\n|<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/commercialstatis05macg|title=Commercial Statistics: A Digest of the Productive Resources, Commercial Legislation, Customs Tariffs, of All Nations. Including All British Commercial Treaties with Foreign States|last=Macgregor|first=John|date=1850|publisher=Whittaker and Company|isbn=|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/commercialstatis05macg/page/18 18]|language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n|1827\n|{{Center|{{en dash}}}}\n|{{Center|{{en dash}}}}\n|~7,420,000\n|<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TrcTAAAAQAAJ|title=The british cyclopedia of literature, history,geography, law ,and politics.|last=partington|first=charles F.|date=1836|publisher=|isbn=|location=|pages=553|language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n|1828\n|6,177,598\n|{{Center|{{en dash}}}}\n|{{Center|{{en dash}}}}\n|<ref name=\":0\" />\n|-\n|1832\n|{{Center|{{en dash}}}}\n|1,906,033\n|{{Center|{{en dash}}}}\n|<ref name=\":0\" />\n|-\n|1839\n|6,113,259\n|{{Center|{{en dash}}}}\n|~8,000,000\n|<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=X72YMqWnkSsC&pg=PA37|title=Italy in the Making 1815 to 1846|last=Berkeley|first=G. F.-H.|last2=Berkeley|first2=George Fitz-Hardinge|last3=Berkeley|first3=Joan|date=1968|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-07427-8|location=|pages=37|language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n|1840\n|6,117,598\n|~<1,800,000 (est.)\n|7,917,598\n|<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=MrgTAAAAQAAJ&pg=PR18|title=Commercial Statistics: A Digest of the Productive Resources, Commercial Legislation, Customs Tariffs ... of All Nations ...|last=|first=|date=1844|publisher=C. Knight and Company|isbn=|location=|pages=18|language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n|1848\n|6,382,706\n|2,046,610\n|8,429,316\n|<ref name=\":1\" />\n|-\n|1851\n|6,612,892\n|2,041,583\n|8,704,472\n|<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=zSNUAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA246|title=The Popular Encyclopedia: Or, Conversations Lexicon|last=|first=|date=1862|publisher=Blackie|isbn=|location=|pages=246|language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n|1856\n|6,886,030\n|2,231,020\n|9,117,050\n|<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P7lSAAAAcAAJ&pg=PA223|title=Selections from Speeches of Earl Russell 1817 to 1841 and from Despatches 1859 to 1865: With Introductions. In 2 Volumes|last=Russell|first=John|date=1870|publisher=Longmans, Green, and Company|isbn=|location=|pages=223|language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n|1859/60\n|6,986,906\n|2,294,373\n|9,281,279\n|<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=HARPAQAAIAAJ&q=%22The+total+population+of+the+continental+portion+of+the+Kingdom+was+6,986,906,+and+Sicily's+population+was+2,294,373.%22&dq=%22The+total+population+of+the+continental+portion+of+the+Kingdom+was+6,986,906,+and+Sicily's+population+was+2,294,373.%22|title=Mezzogiorno d'Europa|last=|first=|date=1983|publisher=|isbn=|location=|pages=473|language=en}}</ref>\n|}\nThe kingdom had a large population, at least three times as large as any other contemporary [[List of historic states of Italy|Italian state]]. At its peak, the kingdom had a [[military]] 100,000 soldiers strong, and a large [[bureaucracy]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1dlob9r5TH0C&pg=PA77|title=Structuring the State: The Formation of Italy and Germany and the Puzzle of Federalism|last=Ziblatt|first=Daniel|date=2008-01-21|publisher=Princeton University Press|isbn=978-1-4008-2724-4|location=|pages=77|language=en}}</ref> [[Naples]] was the largest city in the kingdom and the third largest city in Europe. The second largest city, [[Palermo]], was the third largest in Italy.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RVoSBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA125|title=Italy in the Age of the Risorgimento 1790 - 1870|last=Hearder|first=Harry|date=2014-07-22|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-87206-1|location=|pages=125\u20136|language=en}}</ref> In the 1800s, the kingdom experienced large population growth, rising from approximately five to seven million.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/betweensaltwater00tomm|url-access=registration|quote=kingdom of the two sicilies population.|title=Between Salt Water and Holy Water: A History of Southern Italy|last=Astarita|first=Tommaso|date=2006-07-17|publisher=W. W. Norton & Company|isbn=978-0-393-25432-7|language=en}}</ref> It held approximately 36% of Italy's population around 1850.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=m_vOBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA18|title=An Economic History of Liberal Italy (Routledge Revivals): 1850-1918|last=Toniolo|first=Gianni|date=2014-10-14|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-317-56953-4|location=|pages=18|language=en}}</ref>\n\nBecause the kingdom did not establish a statistical department until after 1848,<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=j-dXAAAAcAAJ&pg=RA1-PA19|title=House Documents|last=|first=|date=1870|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|isbn=|location=Washington, D.C.|pages=19|language=en}}</ref> most population statistics prior to that year are estimates and censuses undertaken were thought by contemporaries to be inaccurate.<ref name=\":0\" /> \n\n==Geography==\n\n===Departments===\n[[File:Suddivisione amministrativa del Regno delle Due Sicilie.png|thumb|350px|right|Departments and Districts of Kingdom of the Two Sicilies]]\n<!--Rider has a section on the talk page where it belongs-->\nThe peninsula was divided into fifteen departments<ref name=\":9\" /><ref>{{cite book|author=Pompilio Petitti|title= Repertorio amministrativo ossia collezione di leggi, decreti, reali rescritti ecc. sull'amministrazione civile del Regno delle Due Sicilie, vol. 1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gKRBAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA1|year=1851|publisher=Stabilimento Migliaccio|place=[[Napoli]]|page=1|language=Italian}}</ref> and Sicily was divided into seven departments.<ref>{{cite book|author=Pompilio Petitti|title=Repertorio amministrativo ossia collezione di leggi, decreti, reali rescritti ecc. sull'amministrazione civile del Regno delle Due Sicilie, vol. 1|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gKRBAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA4|year=1851|publisher= Stabilimento Migliaccio|place=[[Napoli]]|page=4|language=Italian}}</ref> The island itself had a special administrative status, with its base at [[Palermo]].{{citation needed|date=March 2015}} In 1860, when the Two Sicilies were conquered by the [[Kingdom of Sardinia]], the departments became [[provinces of Italy]], according to the [[Rattazzi law]].{{citation needed|date=March 2015}}\n\n{|\n| valign=\"top\" |\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! \n! width=\"140px\" | Peninsula\n! width=\"210px\" | [[Capital (political)|Capital]]\n|-\n| 1\n| [[File:Coat of Arms of Abruzzo Ultra I (last version).svg|20px]] [[Abruzzo Ultra I]]\n| [[Teramo]]\n|-\n| 2\n| [[File:Coat of Arms of Abruzzo Ultra (wings inverted).svg|20px]] [[Abruzzo Ultra II]]\n| [[L'Aquila|Aquila]]\n|-\n| 3\n| [[File:Coat of Arms of Abruzzo Citra.svg|20px]] [[Abruzzo Citra]]\n| [[Chieti]]\n|-\n| 4\n| [[File:Coat of Arms of Contado di Molise.svg|20px]] [[Contado di Molise]]\n| [[Campobasso]]\n|-\n| 5\n| [[File:Coat of Arms of Terra di Lavoro.svg|20px]] [[Terra di Lavoro]]\n| [[Capua]],<br />[[Caserta]] from 1818 \n|-\n| 6\n| [[File:Coat of Arms of the Province of Naples (historical province).svg|20px]] {{nowrap|[[Province of Naples (1806\u20131860)|Province of Naples]]}}\n| [[Naples]]\n|-\n| 7\n| [[File:Coat of Arms of Principato Ultra.svg|20px]] [[Principato Ultra]]\n| [[Avellino]]{{efn|name=\"Benevento\"}}\n|-\n| 8\n| [[File:Coat of Arms of Principato Citra.svg|20px]] [[Principato Citra]]\n| [[Salerno]]\n|-\n| 9\n| [[File:Coat of Arms of Capitanata.svg|20px]] [[Capitanata]]\n| {{nowrap|originally [[San Severo]],}} {{nowrap|then [[Foggia]]}}\n|-\n| 10\n| [[File:Coat of Arms of Terra di Bari.svg|20px]] [[Terra di Bari]]\n| [[Bari]]\n|-\n| 11\n| [[File:Coat of Arms of Terra d'Otranto.svg|20px]] [[Terra d'Otranto]]\n| [[Lecce]]\n|-\n| 12\n| [[File:Coat of Arms of Basilicata.svg|20px]] [[Basilicata]]\n| [[Potenza]]\n|-\n| 13\n| [[File:Coat of Arms of Calabria Citra.svg|20px]] [[Calabria Citra]]\n| [[Cosenza]]\n|-\n| 14\n| [[File:Coat of Arms of Calabria Ultra.svg|20px]] [[Calabria Ultra II]]\n| [[Catanzaro]]\n|-\n| 15\n| [[File:Coat of Arms of the Province of Reggio-Calabria.svg|20px]] [[Calabria Ultra I]]\n| [[Reggio Calabria|Reggio]]\n|-\n|}\n| width=\"30\" | &nbsp;\n| valign=\"top\" |\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! \n! width=\"140px\" | Insular\n! width=\"210px\" | [[Capital (political)|Capital]]\n|-\n| 16\n| [[File:Caltanissetta-Stemma.png|20px]] [[Province of Caltanissetta (Kingdom of Two Sicilies)|Caltanissetta]]\n| [[Caltanissetta]]\n|-\n| 17\n| [[File:Provincia di Catania-Stemma.svg|20px]] [[Province of Catania (Kingdom of Two Sicilies)|Catania]]\n| [[Catania]]\n|-\n| 18\n| [[Province of Girgenti|Girgenti]]\n| [[Agrigento|Girgenti]]\n|-\n| 19\n|  [[Province of Messina (Kingdom of Two Sicilies)|Messina]]\n| [[Messina]]\n|-\n| 20\n| [[Province of Noto|Noto]]\n| [[Noto]]\n|-\n| 21\n| [[Province of Palermo (Kingdom of Two Sicilies)|Palermo]]\n| [[Palermo]]\n|-\n| 22\n| [[Province of Trapani (Kingdom of Two Sicilies)|Trapani]]\n| [[Trapani]]\n|}\n|}\n{{notelist|refs=\n{{efn|name=\"Benevento\"|The city of [[Benevento]] was formally included in this department, but it was occupied by the [[Papal States]] and was de facto an [[exclave]] of that country.{{citation needed|date=March 2015}}}}\n}}\n\n==Economy==\n{{More citations needed section|date=January 2020}}\n\n===Industry===\nIndustry was the largest source of income if compared with the other preunitarian states{{citation needed|date=August 2019}}. One of the most important industrial complexes in the kingdom was the [[shipyard]] of [[Castellammare di Stabia]], which employed 1800 workers. The engineering factory of [[Pietrarsa]] was the largest industrial plant in the Italian peninsula{{citation needed|date=August 2019}}, producing tools, [[cannon]]s, rails, [[locomotive]]s. The complex also included a school for train drivers, and naval engineers and, thanks to this school, the kingdom was able to replace the English personnel who had been necessary until then. The first [[steamboat]] with [[propellor|screw propulsion]] known in the Mediterranean Sea was the \"Giglio delle Onde\", with mail delivery and passenger transport purposes after 1847.\n\nIn Calabria, the Fonderia Ferdinandea was a large [[foundry]] where cast iron was produced. The [[Reali ferriere ed Officine di Mongiana]] was an iron foundry and [[weapon]]s factory. Founded in 1770, it employed 1600 workers in 1860 and closed in 1880.  In Sicily (near [[Catania]] and [[Agrigento]]), [[sulfur]] was mined to make [[gunpowder]]. The Sicilian mines were able to satisfy most of the global demand for sulfur. [[Silk]] cloth production was focused in [[San Leucio]] (near [[Caserta]]). The region of [[Basilicata]] also had several mills in [[Potenza]] and [[San Chirico Raparo]], where [[cotton]], [[wool]] and silk were processed.  [[food industry|Food processing]] was widespread, especially near [[Naples]] ([[Torre Annunziata]] and [[Gragnano]]).<!-- Deleted because just too incredible and unsourced. Reinstate if a source can be produced: \"Almost 99% of the industries present in the Kingdom were destroyed and relocated to the north by the occupying forces of the [[House of Savoy]] after the unification.\" --> \n\n==== Sulfur ====\n{{Main|Sulphur Crisis of 1840}}\nThe kingdom maintained a large [[sulfur]] mining industry. In [[Industrial Revolution|industrializing]] Britain, with the repeal of [[Tariff|tariffs]] on salt in 1824, demand for sulfur from Sicily surged upward. The increasing British control and exploitation of the mining, refining, and transportation of the sulfur, coupled with the failure of this lucrative export to transform Sicily's backward and impoverished economy, led to the 'Sulfur Crisis' of 1840, when [[Ferdinand II of the Two Sicilies|King Ferdinand II]] gave a monopoly of the sulfur industry to a French firm, violating an earlier 1816 trade agreement with Britain. A peaceful solution was eventually negotiated by France.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Thomson|first1=D. W.|date=April 1995|title=Prelude to the Sulphur War of 1840: The Neapolitan Perspective|journal=European History Quarterly|volume=25|issue=2|pages=163\u2013180|doi=10.1177/026569149502500201}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=wZg4ecXXmNYC|title=Sicily and the Unification of Italy: Liberal Policy and Local Power, 1859\u20131866|author=Riall, Lucy|date=1998|publisher=Oxford University Press|isbn=9780191542619|accessdate=7 February 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Transport===\n[[File:Italia ferrovie 1861.03.17.png|thumb|Rail lines of the Italian Peninsula in 1861]]\n[[File:Italia ferrovie 1870 09 20.png|thumb|Rail lines in Italy in 1870]]\nWith all of its major cities boasting successful ports{{citation needed|date=August 2019}}, transport and trade in the Kingdom of the Two Sicilies was most efficiently conducted by sea. The Kingdom possessed the largest merchant fleet in the Mediterranean. Urban road conditions were to the best European standards{{citation needed|date=August 2019}}, by 1839, the main streets of Naples were gas-lit. Efforts were made to tackle the tough mountainous terrain, Ferdinand II built the cliff-top road along the Sorrentine peninsula. Road conditions in the interior and hinterland areas of the kingdom made internal trade difficult. The first railways and iron-suspension bridges in Italy were developed in the south, as was the first overland electric telegraph cable{{citation needed|date=August 2019}}.\n\n===Technological and scientific achievements===\nThe kingdom achieved several scientific and technological accomplishments, such as the first steamboat in the Mediterrean Sea (1818),<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=HDNXAAAAYAAJ&q=%22the+Bourbon+kingdom+of+the+Two+Sicilies+boasted+a+stake+in+shipbuilding,+textiles+and+railway+engines.TheMediterranean's+first+steamboat+was+launched+from+Naples+in+1818.%22&dq=%22the+Bourbon+kingdom+of+the+Two+Sicilies+boasted+a+stake+in+shipbuilding,+textiles+and+railway+engines.TheMediterranean's+first+steamboat+was+launched+from+Naples+in+1818.%22|title=The Economist|last=|first=|date=1975|publisher=Economist Newspaper Limited|isbn=|location=|pages=|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/?id=aYcUQ4XRqOoC&pg=PA20&dq=Mediterranean's+first+steamboat+%221818%22#v=onepage&q=Mediterranean's%20first%20steamboat%20%221818%22&f=false|title=Naval Warfare, 1815-1914|last=Sondhaus|first=Lawrence|date=2012-10-12|publisher=Routledge|isbn=978-1-134-60994-9|location=|pages=20|language=en}}</ref> built in the shipyard of Stanislao Filosa al ponte di Vigliena, near Naples,{{Citation needed|date=December 2019}} and the first [[railway]] in the Italian peninsula (1839), which [[Naples\u2013Portici railway|connected Naples to Portici]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.historytoday.com/archive/la-dolce-vita-italy-rail-1839-1914|title=La Dolce Vita? Italy By Rail, 1839-1914 {{!}} History Today|last=|first=|date=|website=History Today|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-29}}</ref> However, until the Italian unification, the railway development was highly limited. In the year 1859, the kingdom had only 99 kilometers of rail, compared to the 850 kilometers of [[Kingdom of Piedmont-Sardinia|Piedmont]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/concisehistoryof00dugg|url-access=registration|title=A Concise History of Italy|last=Duggan|first=Christopher|date=1994|publisher=Cambridge University Press|isbn=978-0-521-40848-6|location=|pages=[https://archive.org/details/concisehistoryof00dugg/page/152 152]|language=en}}</ref> This was because the kingdom could count on a very large and efficient merchant navy, which was able to compensate for the need for railways. Also, southern landscape was mainly mountainous making the process of building railways quite difficult, as building railway tunnels was much harder at the time.{{citation needed|date=August 2019}} Other achievements included the first volcano observatory in the world, [[Vesuvius Observatory|l'Osservatorio Vesuviano]] (1841),<ref>{{Cite journal|last=De Lucia|first=Maddalena|last2=Ottaiano|first2=Mena|last3=Limoncelli|first3=Bianca|last4=Parlato|first4=Luigi|last5=Scala|first5=Omar|last6=Siviglia|first6=Vittoria|date=2010|title=The Museum of Vesuvius Observatory and its public. Years 2005 - 2008|journal=EGUGA|language=en|volume=|pages=2942|bibcode=2010EGUGA..12.2942D}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.wired.com/2009/06/volcano-profile-mt-vesuvius/|title=Volcano Profile: Mt. Vesuvius|last=Klemetti|first=Erik|date=2009-06-07|work=Wired|access-date=2019-12-29|issn=1059-1028}}</ref>. The rails for the first Italian railways were built in Mongiana as well. All the rails of the old railways that went from the south to as far as [[Bologna]] were built in Mongiana. {{citation needed|date=March 2015}}\n\n==Monarchy==\n\n===Kings of the Two Sicilies===\n{{Main|Monarchs of the Two Sicilies|Monarchs of Sicily|Monarchs of Naples}}\n\n<gallery>\nFile:Ferdinand i twosicilies.jpg|[[Ferdinand I of the Two Sicilies|Ferdinand I]], 1816\u20131825\nFile:Francis I of the Two Sicilies.jpg|[[Francis I of the Two Sicilies|Francis I]], 1825\u20131830\nFile:Fernando II de las Dos Sicilias 2.jpg|[[Ferdinand II of the Two Sicilies|Ferdinand II]], 1830\u20131859\nFile:Ignoto, Ritratto di Francesco II, 1859. Caserta, Palazzo Reale.jpg|[[Francis II of the Two Sicilies|Francis II]], 1859\u20131861\n</gallery>\nIn 1860\u201361 with influence from Great Britain and [[Gladstone's]] propaganda, the kingdom was absorbed into the [[Kingdom of Sardinia]], and the title dropped. It is still claimed by the head of the [[House of Bourbon-Two Sicilies]].\n\n===Titles of King of the Two Sicilies===\nFrancis I or Francis II, King of the Two Sicilies, of [[King of Jerusalem|Jerusalem]], etc., [[Duchy of Parma|Duke of Parma]], Piacenza, [[Duchy of Castro|Castro]], etc., Hereditary Grand Prince of Tuscany, etc.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FsXEdzv7ZzIC&pg=PA250|title=Treaties and Other International Acts of the United States of America: Documents 173-200: 1855-1858|last=States|first=United|date=1931|publisher=U.S. Government Printing Office|isbn=|location=|pages=250|language=en}}</ref>\n\n==House of Bourbon in exile==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=April 2018}}\nSome sovereigns continued to maintain diplomatic relations with the exiled court, including the [[Franz Joseph I of Austria|Emperor of Austria]], the Kings of Bavaria, W\u00fcrttemberg and Hanover, the Queen of Spain, the [[Alexander II of Russia|Emperor of Russia]], and the Papacy. {{When|date=March 2015}}\n\n==Flags of the Kingdom of the Two Sicilies==\n{{Unreferenced section|date=April 2018}}\n<gallery class=\"center\">\nImage:Flag of the Kingdom of the Two Sicilies (1738).svg|1816\u20131848; 1849\u20131860 flag\nImage:Flag of the Kingdom of the Two Sicilies (1848).svg|1848\u20131849 flag\nImage:Flag of the Kingdom of the Two Sicilies (1860).svg|1860\u20131861 flag\n</gallery>\n\n[[File:Arms of the flag of two sicilies.png|center|thumb|600px|Description of the arms appearing in the flag.  Corrections: the upper part of the block marked \"[[Flanders]]\" is Burgundy Ancient; Burgundy Modern (as it is called in English; shown here as New Burgundy) includes a red-and-white border; the block marked \"Aragon Two Sicilies\" is only for Sicily proper (the other \"Sicily\" being the Angevin kingdom of Naples).]]\n\n==Orders of knighthood==\n*[[Order of St. Januarius]]\n*[[Sacred Military Constantinian Order of Saint George]]\n*[[Order of Saint George and Reunion]]\n*[[Order of Saint Ferdinand and Merit]]\n*[[Royal Order of Francis I]]\n\n==Further reading==\n*''[[The Volcano Lover]]'', a novel by [[Susan Sontag]], is set in the Kingdom of the Two Sicilies during the Napoleonic era.\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Italy}}\n* [[Dictatorship of Garibaldi]]\n* [[List of historic states of Italy]]\n* [[List of monarchs of the Kingdom of the Two Sicilies]]\n* [[Southern Italy]]\n* [[Southern Italy autonomist movements]]\n* [[Two Sicilies national football team]]\n* [[Army of the Two Sicilies]]\n* [[Real Marina (Kingdom of the Two Sicilies)]]\n* [[Line of succession to the former throne of the Kingdom of the Two Sicilies]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Alio, Jacqueline. ''Sicilian Studies: A Guide and Syllabus for Educators'' (2018), 250 pp.\n* Eckaus, Richard S. \"The North-South differential in Italian economic development.\" ''Journal of Economic History'' (1961) 21#3 pp: 285\u2013317.\n* Finley, M. I., Denis Mack Smith and Christopher Duggan, '' A History of Sicily'' (1987) abridged one-volume version of 3-volume set of 1969)\n* Imbruglia, Girolamo, ed. ''Naples in the eighteenth century: The birth and death of a nation state'' (Cambridge University Press, 2000)\n* Petrusewicz, Marta. \"Before the Southern Question: 'Native' Ideas on Backwardness and Remedies in the Kingdom of Two Sicilies, 1815\u20131849.\" in ''Italy's 'Southern Question''' (Oxford: Berg, 1998) pp: 27\u201350.\n* Pinto, Carmine. \"The 1860 disciplined Revolution. The Collapse of the Kingdom of the Two Sicilies.\" ''Contemporanea'' (2013) 16#1 pp: 39\u201368.\n* Riall, Lucy. ''Sicily and the Unification of Italy: Liberal Policy & Local Power, 1859\u20131866'' (1998), 252pp\n* Zamagni, Vera. ''The economic history of Italy 1860\u20131990'' (Oxford University Press, 1993)\n\n==External links==\n*{{in lang|it}} [http://www.ilportaledelsud.org/ Brigantino \u2013 Il portale del Sud], a massive Italian-language site dedicated to the history, culture and arts of southern Italy\n*{{in lang|it}} [http://www.editorialeilgiglio.it/ Casa Editoriale Il Giglio], an Italian publisher that focuses on history, culture and the arts in the Two Sicilies\n*{{in lang|it}} [http://www.vocedimegaride.it/ La Voce di Megaride], a website by Marina Salvadore dedicated to Napoli and Southern Italy\n*{{in lang|it}} [http://www.angelomanna.it/ Associazione culturale \"Amici di Angelo Manna\"], dedicated to the work of <!--?: volcanic--> Angelo Manna, historian, poet and deputy\n*{{in lang|it}} [http://www.eleaml.altervista.org/index.html Fora! The e-journal of Nicola Zitara], professor; includes many articles about southern Italy's culture and history\n*[http://www.regalis.com/ Regalis], a website on Italian dynastic history, with sections on the House of the Two Sicilies\n\n\n{{The Bourbons of Naples and Sicily (1735\u20131816)}}\n{{Kings and Princes of